<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rightists Free Colombia Lawmaker  </HEADLINE>
By JUAN PABLO TORO
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A right-wing paramilitary group freed a
Colombian senator and former guerrilla Wednesday, a day after his
family reported he had been killed, officials and relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker, Carlos Alonso Lucio, had fled to Cuba two years
ago to escape criminal charges, but had secretly returned to
Colombia and was seized by paramilitary fighters.
</P>
<P>
   He was abducted while conducting sensitive negotiations between
leftist rebels and the militias headed by Carlos Castano, the
national paramilitary chief said in a letter faxed to local
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   But Castano said Lucio had been an unreliable and pro-rebel
intermediary in the contacts with Colombia's second-largest leftist
insurgency, the National Liberation Army, or ELN.
</P>
<P>
   Without detailing the substance of the talks between the bitter
rivals, Castano said Lucio was trying to make him appear ''weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Following his release in the rugged Andes mountains of Cordoba
State, Lucio was flown to Bogota and taken to jail after giving a
news conference at which he blasted the proceedings against him and
portrayed himself as a ''resurrected'' champion of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want to tell Colombia that I made a bet on peace and I
lost,'' said an exhausted-looking Lucio.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio, 35, said he had slipped back into the country in January
and headed to the mountains to try and facilitate peace talks. He
did not give details on his dealings with Castano and the ELN.
</P>
<P>
   He said he held no ill feelings toward the militia boss, and
even urged that the paramilitary groups be included in peace
negotiations which until now have only involved the government and
two large guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
   Castano faces numerous indictments for assassinations of
left-wing politicians and human rights workers, as well as
massacres committed by men under his command.
</P>
<P>
   President Andres Pastrana has said he is not prepared to
negotiate with the landowner-backed rightists, who have committed
widespread civilian massacres in a scorched-earth campaign against
suspected rebel supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Government and ELN negotiators are scheduled to meet next week,
however, in Switzerland in the first major talks with the group in
nearly two years. Pastrana is also negotiating with a larger
insurgency, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Lucio's father and a member of Lucio's nationalist
political movement reported the senator had been abducted and
executed on Castano's orders.
</P>
<P>
   An ultra-nationalist, Lucio is best known for his fervent
opposition to extraditing Colombian drug suspects to the United
States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
