<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers Hope To Lure Back Lindros  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Eric Lindros has yet to sign a qualifying
offer from the Philadelphia Flyers, and general manager Bob Clarke
hopes the star center looks past their contentious relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ''I talked to Eric the day of the draft, from the draft table
and explained that he doesn't have to like me, but he does play for
his teammates,'' Clarke said Wednesday in a television interview on
Comcast SportsNet, which is owned by the same company that owns the
Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a good team. This is a good city to play hockey in,
and we hoped he'd come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, still recovering from his sixth concussion, has until
Aug. 1 to decide whether to sign the $8.5 million qualifying offer.
However, the offer includes a two-way contract that would allow the
Flyers to send Lindros to their AHL affiliate, the Philadelphia
Phantoms, and pay him a minor-league salary of $85,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Lindros family reportedly was insulted by the offer. In
making the two-way offer, the Flyers invoked a clause in the
collective bargaining agreement which states that a qualifying
offer to a restricted free agent can be a two-way offer if the
player has played fewer than 60 games the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   ''The league wanted us to follow the rules,'' Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros played 55 games last season because of various injuries,
including four concussions sustained in slightly more than four
months. He would have to clear waivers before getting sent to the
Phantoms.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros is scheduled to see Dr. James Kelly, a concussion expert
in Chicago who has been treating him, a few days before the
deadline to sign the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm feeling a lot better. I'm seeing the doctor the end of
this month. I'll play when everything is clear,'' Lindros recently
told the London Ontario Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, whose younger brother Brett was forced to retire
because of concussions, has considered retirement or possibly
sitting out up to a full year. He has also mentioned playing in
Europe where the style of play is less physical.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is more to life than just hockey,'' Lindros said.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros' relationship with Clarke, his childhood hero,
deteriorated this season to a point where the two didn't speak for
months.
</P>
<P>
   The boiling point came after Lindros criticized the team's
medical staff for failing to diagnose his second concussion of the
season on March 4.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke then stripped Lindros of his captaincy, and he was
ostracized from the team until he returned for Games 6 and 7 of the
Eastern Conference finals against the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've always said all along that with him, (Keith) Primeau,
(Daymond) Langkow and (Kent) Manderville, with centers like that,
we'd have the best center ice in the league by a long ways and we'd
have a legitimate shot at winning the Stanley Cup and I think
that's what every player's goal is,'' Clarke said. ''It'd be nice
if we got along, but it's not necessary in my opinion. You're a
hockey player, you play for your coach and your teammates. Lots of
players don't like their managers, but you still play for your
teammates and that's what we encourage him to look at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
