<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, July 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Camp David Summit Collapses After 9 Days
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- An exhaustive effort to break through a half-century of
Palestinian-Israeli conflict ended in failure Wednesday night at the wooded
presidential sanctuary that had lent its name to historic success in Middle East
peace. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
could not come to terms after nine days of talks shepherded by President
Clinton, and all three headed out from the Camp David retreat in a dismal rain
that matched the day's mood. Clinton, his face sagging with weariness during
several practically all-night sessions, returned to the White House to prepare
to fly almost immediately to Japan for an international economic conference.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chinese Police Arrest Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Police swiftly broke up scattered Falun Gong protests on
Thursday morning, punching some of the protesters and dragging them into vans on
the first anniversary of the crackdown on the meditation group. About 67 people
were rounded up in Tiananmen Square. Most demonstrated individually or in small
groups. Thursday's display showed that one of China's biggest political
campaigns in years may have thinned the resilient group's ranks but has failed
to wipe the movement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Discusses Setting Up New State
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The democratically elected government toppled during
Fiji's two-month hostage crisis met Thursday to discuss setting up a new state
in the western part of the country, Fiji radio said. The meeting came a day
after coup leader George Speight reportedly forced a delay in the Fiji's new
Cabinet taking office, a move that raised concern of a return to the civil
unrest that has plagued this Pacific island nation. Speight threw Fiji into
crisis on May 19 when he led an armed gang into Parliament and took dozens of
lawmakers hostage.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush on Verge of Picking VP
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- George W. Bush said wednesday he was on the verge of
picking his running mate and suggested that a vice presidential candidate should
pose little political risk to the ticket. ''You want somebody who's not going to
hurt you,'' Bush said. Twelve days before the opening of the national convention
that will formally make him the Republican presidential candidate, Bush told
reporters at an impromptu news conference, ''I will make up my mind soon.'' A
number of Republicans are urging the Texan to sit on his lead in polls and make
a ''safe'' pick.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House OKs Raising IRA Contributions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House overwhelmingly passed a bill raising
contribution limits for individual retirement accounts and 401(k)s Wednesday,
hoping to boost Americans' anemic savings rate. President Clinton said the
measure doesn't do enough for low-income people but did not threaten a veto. The
House voted 401-25 to send the measure to the Senate, with 182 Democrats joining
nearly all Republicans in favor. Senate supporters say they will push for action
in early September. Sponsors called the bill a partial answer to a U.S. savings
rate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mandela Pushes for Burundi Peace
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) -- After a day of talks Wednesday to end Burundi's
seven-year civil war, mediator Nelson Mandela said two issues were standing in
the way of peace: who will lead the transitional government and when the
cease-fire should begin. The former South African president is overseeing the
negotiations between Burundian officials and opposition leaders. He is pressing
to get 19 separate delegations to agree to a power-sharing agreement he hopes
will be signed by the end of August.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Temperatures Still Sizzle in South
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Mechanic William Kilpatrick soldiered through
another day of 100-degree heat in an outdoor garage area Wednesday, hoping for a
break from searing temperatures that were smashing records in Alabama and baking
much of the South. The heat wave that has covered much of the South for the past
two weeks has been blamed for the deaths of at least 12 people in Texas and four
in Louisiana.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 44; Nasdaq Falls 122
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices tumbled Wednesday, as disappointed investors
vented their wrath on a slew of technology companies. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed down 43.84 at 10,696.08. The Nasdaq composite index was down
121.54 at 4,055.63. Japanese financial markets are closed Thursday for a
national holiday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reds 4, Astros 0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Pete Harnisch pitched a four-hitter for his second straight
complete game, leading the Cincinnati Reds over the Houston Astros 4-0 Wednesday
night. Barry Larkin hit a solo homer to fuel a three-run sixth inning, then
tripled in the seventh and scored on a sacrifice fly by Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
