<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Diamond Industry Steps Out  </HEADLINE>
By ANGELA CHARLTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- At mine offices on the Arctic permafrost and in
hushed vaults in Moscow's best-guarded buildings, the eyes of
Russia's diamond producers glint with optimism. This country, they
say, is primed to reap rewards from recent upheaval in the global
diamond industry.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is the world's second-largest diamond producer, but
Soviet-era restrictions and the De Beers cartel have crimped
Russian profits from the gems.
</P>
<P>
   Now South Africa-based De Beers is relaxing its grip on the
world's diamonds, and Russia is angling to make a name for itself
in the lucrative, secretive industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time for Russia to step out in this business,'' said
Natalya Marakina, a member of the exclusive Russian Diamond
Chamber, a club for diamond producers. ''We are ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has an advantage these days, as fears mushroom about gem
sales financing the wars in Sierra Leone, Angola and Congo. It
tarnished the meeting in Belgium of the World Diamond Congress,
which announced strict new measures Wednesday to clamp down on the
trade in ''Conflict diamonds.'' The issue is also on the agenda of
the Group of Eight summit in Okinawa, Japan, which begins Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Russians are an important source of non-bloodied stones,''
said John Meyer, an industry analyst with Societe Generale in
London. ''The diamond industry in Russia has had a pretty low
profile ... and this could be a pretty good marketing tool for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia produces about 20 percent of the world's rough diamonds --
$1.5 billion worth in 1999 -- and has vast untapped reserves.
</P>
<P>
   In Marakina's sanguine scenario, Russia's diamond monopoly
Alrosa would develop new mines and reach more markets. More exports
would bring increased government revenues -- the state owns a
majority stake of Alrosa -- and good news for an economy still hung
over from a decade of decline.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry is shackled by inefficiency and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Most Russian diamonds come from Sakha, formerly known as
Yakutia, a province five times the size of Texas that straddles the
Arctic Circle. Soviet authorities coaxed workers to the ever-frozen
wilderness with bloated salaries and generous benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Alrosa has trimmed the work force, but production costs remain
high -- about five times as much as De Beers spends extracting
stones from its South African deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Once they leave Yakutia, diamonds are guarded by a series of
private militias. Addresses of the Moscow vaults are a prized
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Yet smuggling abounds, and Russia's notoriously weak and corrupt
law enforcement officials are nearly powerless to stem it,
prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   The former head of the government's gem and precious metals
agency, Yevgeny Bychkov, has been charged with smuggling $183
million worth of diamonds and gold out of Russia to a San Francisco
company. He denies the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the increased diamond activity that Alrosa wants
would only invite more crime.
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle to development is the lack of investment,
because the Russian diamond industry clings to strict rules barring
foreigners from exporting the gems. In May, De Beers pulled out of
its only investment project in Russia, the Lomonosov field near the
Arctic city of Arkhangelsk, citing disputes with local officials.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Alrosa says it's ready to take advantage of the
industry's latest transformation.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers has stockpiled most of the world's diamonds since the
1930s to keep them rare and expensive. With profitability down and
its market share slipping, the company announced last week that it
would slash its stockpile and focus on boosting demand through a
new marketing arm called the Diamond Trading Company.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government said Friday that it would not renew its
agreement with De Beers when it expires next year. The contract
puts a strict cap on Russian exports, and critics say it is
stunting Russia's mining and cutting industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''After 40 years in the diamond business, Russia has grown out
of children's shorts and understands how to sell diamonds so as not
to harm the market or our own interests,'' said Valery Rudakov,
chief of Russia's precious gem reserves.
</P>
<P>
   But Alrosa's President Vyacheslav Shtyrov insisted Monday that
Russia isn't planning to sever ties with De Beers, and proposed
that his company buy a stake in De Beers' new Diamond Trading
Company.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers is keen to keep Russia on its side so the market won't
be flooded with gems.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russia is a long-standing partner,'' said company spokesman
Andy Lamont. ''If we can succeed in this new strategy it will be
good for all partners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 0119 </TRAILER>
