<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Is Mexico's Fox President or CEO?  </HEADLINE>
By MARK STEVENSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The introduction of New Coke may have been a
mere marketing ploy for Coca-Cola, but for Mexico's new
president-elect it was a formative moment. Vicente Fox learned much
about political strategy during the cola wars of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising. Fox, a former top Coca-Cola executive,
calls his constituents ''clients,'' promises ''total quality'' and
sees himself more as a good manager than as a politician.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the stories Fox told me was about how Coca-Cola
introduced New Coke, and people didn't accept it,'' recalls a top
adviser, Adolfo Aguilar Zinser.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's marketing chiefs decided to hold firm as sales dropped,
then reintroduce the traditional cola flavor, and watch sales
rebound to higher than when the campaign started.
</P>
<P>
   That helped Fox learn ''how to stand still, not loose his temper
or spirit, because he will begin to figure out how to jump back,''
Aguilar Zinser said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox often comes across like a ''how to succeed in business''
manual, contrasting sharply with the paternal, almost monarchical
air of seven decades of his predecessors for the Mexican
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''I read a lot of business books, a lot,'' Fox said, although he
was vague when asked which business leader most influenced his
style: ''Many, many of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest round in the transition to what some analysts call
Fox's vision of ''Mexico, Inc.'' came at a news conference two
weeks after he became the first opposition presidential candidate
in 71 years to defeat the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   Fox pledged to run the government on a ''matrix-style management
plan, which is used in many organizations'' -- but which is a
mystery to most Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   Matrix management, a corporate fad begun in the 1960s,
establishes overlapping lines of responsibility, making employees
report to several bosses.
</P>
<P>
   A meta-manager -- in Fox's case, a Cabinet-level adviser -- would
be put in charge of promoting a ''product line'' -- an issue like
poverty or education -- across government departments as disparate
as tax collection, commerce and foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
   Would that make Fox a distant CEO, delegating authority to his
managers?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. ''Matrix management also guarantees that top
managers must step in to resolve the very conflicts and disputes
guaranteed by the organizational design,'' analyst Michael Schrage
noted in a 1998 article.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it is quite a switch for Mexicans, used to a sort of
rarified, high-flown political rhetoric about the ''motherland''
and the ''historical conquests'' of the Mexican Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can learn a new political language, but the country is not
a corporation,'' said author and pundit Carlos Monsivais, who
claims Fox wants to treat the government as ''a mega holding
company.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't float a country on the stock exchange. If you do a
cost-benefit analysis on culture, it would get cut right out,''
Monsivais said.
</P>
<P>
   Such mistrust doesn't seem to faze Fox, who ''thinks that what
he provides is, more than anything, administrative skills,'' said
Aguilar Zinser, who is now a member of Fox's transition team.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever he goes to see a leader anywhere in the world, the
first thing he asks is, 'How do you handle taxes?' He very seldom
asks about politics,'' Aguilar Zinser said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who has sent out corporate headhunters to search for his
top aides, wants to choose his Cabinet ''as if he was recruiting
the CEO of Ford, G.M., CBS or NBC,'' Aguilar Zinser said.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to estimate how great the change will be in
Mexican political culture, long a nest of intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians who used vagueness as a shield -- the economy might
be full of ''bright spots and dark spots,'' or ''red lights and
yellow lights'' -- are likely to give way to painfully technical
discussions of decentralization and tax policy.
</P>
<P>
   Monsivais recalled an old saying that the only phrase one needs
in Mexican politics is ''Get them before they get you.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Now,'' Monsivais quipped, ''the only word that Mexican
politics will know how to conjugate is 'efficiency.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 0120 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
