<HEADLINE> Text of Mideast Summit  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Text of President Clinton's remarks on the Camp David
summit, as
transcribed by The Associated Press.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As all of you know, for the past nine days we have been engaged
in the most comprehensive and total negotiations ever between
Palestinians and Israelis on the core issues of their 52-year
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties have been making an intensive effort to resolve
their differences over their most difficult issues. The gaps remain
substantial, but there has been progress, and we must all be
prepared to go the extra mile.
</P>
<P>
   After a round of intensive consultations this evening, the
parties agreed to stay at Camp David while I travel to Okinawa for
the G8 summit.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Lockhart will be able to fill you in on the details on how
this occurred. I have to take the plane and I'm running late, but I
do want to explain what happened.
</P>
<P>
   During the time I am gone, Secretary Albright will be working
with the parties and we'll continue to try to close the gaps. Upon
my return I will assess the status of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   There should be no illusion about the difficult task ahead, that
there should be no limit to the effort we're prepared to make.
</P>
<P>
   These are in fundamental ways the hardest peace issues I have
ever dealt with. But the short answer that we are still here after
everybody thought we were through is that nobody wanted to give up.
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, as hard as these issues are, they don't
want to give up, and I don't think we should give up. And so we're
still plugging away.
</P>
<P>
   But, so you should draw no inference from this, I will observe
the news blackout on the details and I will continue to do it, but
this is really, really hard.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you very much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
