<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers 3, Angels 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Right fielder Scarborough Green threw out
Scott Spiezio at the plate to end the game Wednesday night,
preserving the Texas Rangers' 3-2 win over the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   With Spiezio on second base and two outs, Kevin Stocker singled.
Green fielded the ball and threw on the fly to catcher Ivan
Rodriguez, who made the tag.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler homered and Dave Martinez had a pair of RBI singles
as the Rangers ended a three-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers (10-7) won for the seventh time in nine decisions,
allowing two runs and eight hits in 6 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander, trying to avoid losing three consecutive starts
for the second time this season -- and second time in his 12-year
career -- struck out six, walked one and picked two runners off
first base.
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland pitched the ninth and got his 24th save, thanks
to Green's throw.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, whose single to center in the fourth drove in
Rodriguez with the game's first run, put Texas ahead in the sixth
with a single off Kent Bottenfield (6-8). Rodriguez had led off the
inning with the Rangers' major league-leading 199th double.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler made it 3-1 in the seventh with a leadoff homer, his
fifth of the season and first on the road. He had his second
three-hit game.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio sliced Texas' lead to 3-2 in the seventh with a two-out
RBI single. Edgard Clemente followed with a double, putting runners
at second and third and chasing Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Davis relieved, walked major league hit leader Darin Erstad
intentionally, then retired Stocker on a grounder to end the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who has given up at least 10 hits in each of his
previous three starts, leads all AL pitchers with 158 hits allowed.
He was working on a one-hit shutout when rookie Bengie Molina
homered in the sixth to tie it at 1.
</P>
<P>
   It was Molina's 12th homer -- the most by an Angels catcher since
Lance Parrish hit 19 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, trying to win three consecutive starts for the
first time since joining the Angels in a trade for All-Star center
fielder Jim Edmonds on March 23, was charged with three runs and
eight hits in seven innings. The right-hander, who failed to strike
out a batter for the first time in his 19 starts this season, has
surrendered at least one home run in 10 of his last 12 starts
outings and 22 altogether.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Angels RF Tim Salmon, whose attempt at a sliding catch on
Sunday aggravated an already sore area in his left shoulder that
had bothered him for two weeks, pinch-ran for Mo Vaughn in the
eighth. ... Erstad, who began the game 10-for-29 lifetime against
Rogers, went 0-for-4. ... Molina called a pitchout in the sixth and
caught Martinez trying to steal second. It was the 24th baserunner
Molina has thrown out trying to steal in 65 attempts this season.
... Scott Schoeneweis, who hasn't pitched for the Angels since June
16 because of a strained right rib cage muscle, threw 79 pitches in
a seven-inning rehab start for Triple-A Edmonton against Oklahoma.
He allowed an unearned run and two hits while striking out six, and
did not get a decision in the Trappers' 2-1 loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
