<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes $288B Defense Bill  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved a $20 billion increase in
Pentagon spending for next year, including pay raises designed to
keep men and women from leaving the military for civilian life.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 367-58, the House Wednesday approved a compromise
$288 billion defense appropriations bill and sent it to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, said the legislation ''provides the
funding for the security and defense of the United States and
assures that our military strength remains second to none.''
</P>
<P>
   The pay raise, he said, is of ''great importance especially for
younger military members with families and for mid-career personnel
who are considering abandoning the military for the civilian
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill spends nearly $20 billion more on Pentagon programs in
the year starting Oct. 1 than this year and $3.3 billion more than
requested by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just the increase in this bill is larger than the entire
foreign aid bill and the interior appropriations bill,'' said Rep.
David R. Obey, D-Wis., adding that the United States spends more on
defense than Russia, China, Iran, North Korea and Libya combined.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are going to do that, we have an obligation to take care
of our other national priorities and make sure the accounting is
... forthright,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Obey asserted that the additional money goes ''not where it is
needed militarily'' to improve readiness but rather to award
defense contracts in states where it will help legislators
politically.
</P>
<P>
   A focus of the appropriations debate this year was to make
military life more attractive and thus stem the flow of men and
women from the armed forces to civilian jobs in the booming U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The bill includes a 3.7 percent military pay raise and 9 percent
increase -- $988 million more than last year -- for military health
care.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the bill worked out late last week by a Senate-House
conference committee includes $75.8 billion for military personnel;
$100 billion for operations, maintenance and working capital funds;
$59 billion for weapons procurement, $41.4 billion for research and
development and $14 billion for other Department of Defense
programs and classified amounts for foreign intelligence activities
by the department, CIA and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Other specific items include:
</P>
<P>
   --$1.8 billion in emergency supplemental funds for this year,
partly to continue paying for operations in the Balkans and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   --$1.5 billion to help the Army quickly develop two new
4,000-person ''medium brigades'' that can deploy to the world's hot
spots within 96 hours.
</P>
<P>
   --$4 billion to buy and continue research and development on the
F-22 fighter jet program.
</P>
<P>
   --$12.1 billion for health programs, including research into
breast and prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   --$4 billion for a new aircraft carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4576.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Web site: http://thomas.loc.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 0134 </TRAILER>
