<HEADLINE> Convicted Fund-Raisers Aided Mineta  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Commerce Secretary-designate Norman Mineta
received a handful of contributions in 1992 arranged by a convicted
Democratic fund-raiser who later acknowledged she reimbursed the
donors, congressional investigators' documents show.
</P>
<P>
   There's no evidence Mineta knew of the scheme by fund-raiser
Nora Lum to funnel $4,250 to his House campaign through straw
donors, congressional investigators found.
</P>
<P>
   Only $2,250 of the donations actually reached Mineta's campaign
treasury, Federal Election Commission records show.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Department spokesman Morrie Goodman said Mineta didn't
know about the scheme, and questioned why the fund-raising
documents surfaced the week that the Senate considered his
nomination as the first Asian-American Cabinet secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Lum was a prominent Democratic fund-raiser in the Asian-American
community during the 1992 election. She and her husband Gene were
each sentenced to 10 months confinement and fined $30,000 in 1997
after pleading guilty to a conspiracy charge alleging improper
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   The transactions that resulted in the Lums' prosecution did not
involve Mineta's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Lums disclosed the straw donations to Mineta in a
1997 written offer of testimony to the House Government Reform
Committee, which has been investigating fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The Lums told the committee through their lawyer that they
staged a fund-raiser in October 1992 for Mineta's congressional
campaign. The event was billed as the National California Asian
Pacific Leadership Awards.
</P>
<P>
   In their offer of testimony, the Lums indicated that the Mineta
event did not raise as much money as expected, and they made up the
difference by donating money themselves under other people's names
</P>
<P>
   ''The event fell well short of its goal and the witnesses made
up the difference with conduit contributions,'' the Lums' offer of
testimony said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lums' attorney, Cono Namorato, did not return a call to his
office Wednesday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the donors, Larry Wong, told the House committee in a
July 1998 deposition that Lum asked him to write a $2,000 check to
the Mineta campaign in October 1992. Lum said she would reimburse
him for the donation, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She wrote me a check first and asked me to write a check to
the Mineta campaign, which I did,'' Wong told committee
investigators. Wong told the committee that the check was never
cashed.
</P>
<P>
   Committee documents show that three other people, though listed
as contributing a total of $2,250 to Mineta's campaign, never wrote
checks from their personal accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Lums' offer to testify before the committee was never
formalized in part because Democrats did not want to grant the
couple immunity from prosecution. No charges have been filed
against the Lums concerning those claims.
</P>
<P>
   In their criminal case, the Lums admitted to using ''straw
donors'' to conceal $50,000 in illegal donations. The money went to
the re-election effort of Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and the
unsuccessful congressional candidacy of W. Stuart Price of Oklahoma
in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and Price have said they were unaware of the source of
the donations. The Lums were the first guilty pleas obtained by the
Justice Department's campaign finance task force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
