<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, July 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Camp David Summit Ends Without Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- A nine-day effort to resolve the Palestinian-Israeli
conflict ended Wednesday night without agreement at the wooded presidential
sanctuary that had lent its name to historic success in Middle East peace. Only
hours later, however, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat indicated that they would stay on at Camp David to continue the
talks without President Clinton. ''The summit will continue with Secretary (of
State Madeleine) Albright after discussions that President Clinton had with both
sides in order to try to reach an agreement,'' a senior Israeli official said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Salmon Plan Keeps Snake Dams
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Clinton administration officials said Wednesday they will
not recommend breaching the Snake River dams for at least eight years while they
give a soon-to-be-released salmon recovery plan time to work. Removing the
earthen portions of the four 100-foot-high dams in southeastern Washington state
would be insufficient to recover salmon, would not help Columbia River stocks
and would divert funds from other salmon efforts, said George Frampton, acting
chairman of the White House Council on Environmental Quality.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft To Add Call Software
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. plans to offer free computer-based
long-distance calls in a new version of its MSN Messenger software, due out
Thursday. With the new software, MSN Messenger users will be able to use their
computers to place calls to other computers around the world, or to any number
in the United States or Canada, according to Microsoft product manager Deanna
Sanford. The computer must be connected to the Internet, of course, and must
also have either speakers or earphones as well as a microphone.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chinese Police Arrest Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Police swiftly broke up scattered Falun Gong protests on
Thursday morning, punching some of the protesters and dragging them into vans on
the first anniversary of the crackdown on the meditation group. About 67 people
were rounded up in Tiananmen Square. Most demonstrated individually or in small
groups. Thursday's display showed that one of China's biggest political
campaigns in years may have thinned the resilient group's ranks but has failed
to wipe the movement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Discusses Setting Up New State
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The democratically elected government toppled during
Fiji's two-month hostage crisis met Thursday to discuss setting up a new state
in the western part of the country, Fiji radio said. The meeting came a day
after coup leader George Speight reportedly forced a delay in the Fiji's new
Cabinet taking office, a move that raised concern of a return to the civil
unrest that has plagued this Pacific island nation. Speight threw Fiji into
crisis on May 19 when he led an armed gang into Parliament and took dozens of
lawmakers hostage.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush on Verge of Picking VP
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- George W. Bush said wednesday he was on the verge of
picking his running mate and suggested that a vice presidential candidate should
pose little political risk to the ticket. ''You want somebody who's not going to
hurt you,'' Bush said. Twelve days before the opening of the national convention
that will formally make him the Republican presidential candidate, Bush told
reporters at an impromptu news conference, ''I will make up my mind soon.'' A
number of Republicans are urging the Texan to sit on his lead in polls and make
a ''safe'' pick.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House OKs Raising IRA Contributions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House overwhelmingly passed a bill raising
contribution limits for individual retirement accounts and 401(k)s Wednesday,
hoping to boost Americans' anemic savings rate. President Clinton said the
measure doesn't do enough for low-income people but did not threaten a veto. The
House voted 401-25 to send the measure to the Senate, with 182 Democrats joining
nearly all Republicans in favor. Senate supporters say they will push for action
in early September. Sponsors called the bill a partial answer to a U.S. savings
rate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 44; Nasdaq Falls 122
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices tumbled Wednesday. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed down 43.84 at 10,696.08. The Nasdaq composite index was down
121.54 at 4,055.63. Japanese financial markets are closed Thursday for a
national holiday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White Sox 3, Twins 2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Brook Fordyce broke out of a 1-for-18 slump with three
hits, including a homer, to back the solid pitching of rookie left-hander Mark
Buehrle as the Chicago White Sox won their fifth straight game, 3-2 over
Minnesota on Wednesday night. The White Sox have won 29 of their last 40 games.
</P>
