<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lopez Renews Quest for Women's Open  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. (AP) -- There are so many Nancy Lopez memories at
the U.S. Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing second in 1975 at just 18, a preview to the incredible
career that was to come. Battling Hollis Stacy while trying to hide
a broken zipper. Shooting 60s in all four rounds at Pumpkin Ridge
in 1997, yet still finishing second. Waving the white flag of
surrender at Blackwolf Run.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the memory that Lopez knows so well but has
waited her whole career to live.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I win the U.S. Open, I'm going to camp out on the green and
I'm going to stay out there for a whole night just to enjoy it,''
she said Wednesday. ''I'm just going to stay there and just think
about that last day and that last hole and the crowd and everything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez has been chasing this dream since 1974. Already a member
of the Hall of Fame with 48 career victories and three major
championships, it's the only piece missing from her illustrious
career.
</P>
<P>
   She's come as close as you can possibly get four times and yet
always come up short.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's times when I walk away from a U.S. Open and I just
really want to go slit my wrists because I'm so frustrated because
I've played poorly,'' she said. ''But then you walk away from the
U.S. Open, where you play great golf courses that you really,
really love. And that's what golf is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   She couldn't have known it was going to be like this in 1975,
when she matched strokes with her idol, JoAnne Carner, and finished
second behind Sandra Palmer. Or two years later, when she
challenged Stacy, a three-time Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   But here she is, at 43, still giving chase. The title means so
much she was even willing to qualify for this year's tournament,
which began Thursday at the Merit Club.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she happened to call the U.S. Golf Association office
to see what she needed to do to qualify on the very day officials
were deciding to give her a special exemption.
</P>
<P>
   ''That night, (someone) called me and left a message on my
answering machine and told me they had given me a special exemption
to play the U.S. Open. I was very, very excited,'' she said. ''I
flew through the house trying to find everybody to let them know I
did have the call that I was given a special exemption.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was really, really thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning means so much she even took a lesson, something she'd
never done before -- unless you count the ones her father gave her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel really good right now. I've been hitting the ball
really well,'' she said. ''The way I feel about my game right now,
I feel like I have a good chance to play very well here. And I
certainly would like to get to the top on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't even made the cut the last two years, and she's no
longer considered a favorite for the event. That distinction now
belongs to players like Karrie Webb, Annika Sorenstam and defending
champion Juli Inkster.
</P>
<P>
   But if she ever wonders if she should give up the dream, all she
has to do is remember 1997. Just like this year, Lopez worked hard
before the event, getting her game and body in shape. She shot
69-68-69-69 at Pumpkin Ridge, the only person in the history of the
Women's Open to shoot all four rounds in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   It still wasn't enough, though, as her 20-foot birdie putt that
would have forced a playoff with Alison Nicholas stopped an inch
from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt really good about that one,'' she said. ''That's the
one I felt like I should have taken with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she is here, still hoping to sit on a green Sunday
night and watch the stars.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it would be great,'' Inkster said. ''Everybody would
root for Lopez to win the Open. ... I think everybody in the locker
room would be there, right by her side, rooting for her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 0203 </TRAILER>
