<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney General sues contractors for work never completed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   (Binghamton-AP) -- State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer filed
suit against nine home-improvement contractors for allegedly taking
thousands of dollars in repair bills for jobs that were never
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The list of contractors which Spitzer's office named in lawsuits
Wednesday are only a few of the dozens of firms that state
prosecutors insist have taken money for work that was never
completed.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Spitzer said his office is seeking more than $200,000 in
compensation for people taken in by fraudulent home improvement
schemes that ran the gamut from driveway repaving outfits to
carpenters who took cash in advance and never followed through.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those cases are handled with out of court settlements
and mediation, prosecutors said, as they issued a warning yesterday
to people thinking about hiring workmen to repave driveways or
replace roofs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very keenly aware in the attorney general's office that
the vast majority of contractors are upstanding, hardworking men
and women,'' Spitzer spokesman Marc Violette said. ''We are dealing
today with the very, very small number of people who give
contractors a bad name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-20-00 0210 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000720.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Filly Wins 16 Straight  </HEADLINE>
By ED SCHUYLER Jr.
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was bought sight unseen, and now Hallowed Dreams is sweet
16, a Cajun horse racing queen.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen wins for the unbeaten 3-year-old filly has tied the
record of consecutive victories held by Citation and Cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Lloyd Romero shrugs off comparisons of his filly with
those two great Thoroughbreds. Such comparisons, of course, are
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hear that all the time, but that's OK,'' said the former
Louisiana State trooper, who co-owns Hallowed Dreams.
</P>
<P>
   He also scoffs at criticism that all of Hallowed Dreams' starts
have been in Louisiana, where she was bred -- at Evangeline Downs,
Delta Downs, the Fair Grounds and Louisiana Downs, the Bossier City
track at which she could attempt to break the record in late August
or in September.
</P>
<P>
   ''She belongs to the people of Louisiana,'' said Romero, who
hails from Erath in Cajun country. ''That's God's country.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Romero noted, ''I go to the airport and I see that
planes fly both ways. ''They can fly here from New York. They can
fly here from Kentucky. Let them come here and chase her in
103-degree heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallowed Dreams has led all the way in all but one of her
starts, none longer than 6&AMP;frac12; furlongs
</P>
<P>
   ''I bought her sight unseen when she was 4-months-old,'' Romero
said. ''Her momma (Pacific Dream) was a pretty good horse. She won
$90,000 when purses were $1,500-$2,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Romero and Johnny Gaspard paid $15,000 for Hallowed Dreams, who
has earned $390,429, and they have turned down an offer of $2
million to sell her.
</P>
<P>
   ''How much money do you need,'' the 65-year-old Romero said.
''It only takes $5,000 to bury a man, and I have $5,000. If it was
just an investment, OK, but racing is game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're both really blessed,'' Gaspard said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only Hallowed Dreams, but horse training itself, has been
just what the doctor ordered for Romero, whose son, Randy, was a
top jockey. Another son, Gerald, also trains.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have Parkinson's Disease,'' Romero said. ''It gives me
something to go to work for.''
</P>
<P>
   Romero became a full-time trainer in 1977 after surviving an
accident while still a state policemen. A vehicle driven by a drunk
crashed head-on into his patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   Another whose life has been affected by Hallowed Dreams is
41-year-old jockey Sylvester Carmouche, who was suspended for 10
years by Louisiana racing authorities for winning a mile race in
which his mount, Landing Officer, ran less than a quarter-mile at
Delta Downs in January 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The race was run in a heavy fog. The horses started from a chute
and the race took them through the homestretch twice. Landing
Officer got to the finish line 24 lengths ahead of his closest
pursuer for what briefly was his fourth win in 50 starts.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out, however, that shortly after the break, Carmouche
pulled up Landing Officer, and they lurked the near the top of the
stretch in the fog until the rest of the field came around.
</P>
<P>
   Carmouche was reinstated in 1998 with the help of Romero, and he
became Hallowed Dreams' regular rider in her third start.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thank God so much for giving me something like this and Mr.
Lloyd Romero for thinking of me to ride her,'' Carmouche said after
Hallowed Dreams tied Citation and Cigar's record by winning the
Dixie Miss July 15 at Louisiana Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's part of my family,'' Carmouche said. ''She's just like
my wife. I love her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
