<HEADLINE> National League Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Kevin Brown nearly pitched a one-hitter, while Jeff
D'Amico
tossed a five-hit shutout. It can be argued, however, that the NL's
best-pitched game of the night came from Pete Harnisch.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After all, he tossed the first complete-game shutout ever at
hitter-friendly Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch pitched a four-hitter for his second straight complete
game, leading the Cincinnati Reds over the Houston Astros 4-0 on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch (3-5) beat his old teammates for the fifth straight
time. In his previous start, he pitched the first complete game at
Coors Field this season and snapped the Reds' string of 103 games
without a complete game.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were a lot of circumstances, they just hit balls at
people and I had good stuff the last couple of times out,''
Harnisch said. ''My breaking ball is better. That's the key, to get
them thinking about the breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed only one hit in eight innings, leaving for a
pinch-hitter as Los Angeles was scored five runs in the eighth
inning of a 9-1 victory over Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico pitched his first shutout in three years, winning his
fourth consecutive start as Milwaukee beat Pittsburgh 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   In other games, New York beat Montreal 5-3, Chicago topped
Philadelphia 5-4, Arizona edged St. Louis 4-3 and San Diego downed
San Francisco 4-3 in 10 innings. Atlanta and Florida were rained
out.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch struck out four and walked two in his 11th career
shutout. He has thrown the first back-to-back complete games by a
Reds pitcher since David Wells in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been sharp every game he's pitched,'' Reds manager Jack
McKeon said. ''But the last two times out, this is what we looked
for at the start of the season and didn't have.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last couple of weeks, the other guys have been trying to
follow suit. Maybe he's going to be the guy to look for in the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Larkin hit a solo homer to fuel a three-run sixth inning,
then tripled in the seventh and scored on a sacrifice fly by Ken
Griffey Jr.
Dodgers 9, Rockies 1:
</P>
<P>
   At Los Angeles, Brown showed no ill effects from the tightness
in his pitching shoulder that caused him to be removed from his
last start.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (9-3) allowed only a first-inning single by Larry Walker
before retiring 23 of the last 24 batters he faced -- including the
final 14. He walked one and struck out eight.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hansen, making just his 14th start of the season, hit the
first pitch from Rolando Arrojo (5-8) into the right-field seats
after Shawn Green and Eric Karros hit one-out singles in the sixth.
The homer was Hansen's fifth; the previous four came as a pinch
hitter.
Brewers 6, Pirates 0:
</P>
<P>
   At Milwaukee, D'Amico struck out four and walked four.
</P>
<P>
   In his last four starts, he has allowed just one run in 30 2-3
innings, lowering his ERA to 1.87.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amico (6-4) missed all of 1998 and most of last season after
surgery on his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt good in the bullpen,'' said D'Amico, who was on the
disabled list this season from June 7 through June 30 with
tendinitis in his right shoulder. ''I felt strong and was able to
carry it into the game and was able to go out there and put in a
good performance.''
Mets 5, Expos 3:
</P>
<P>
   At Montreal, pinch-hitter Joe McEwing delivered a two-run single
and scored on Derek Bell's single as the Mets rallied in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Guerrero hit an RBI double that put the Expos ahead 3-2
in the seventh. Bell prevented Montreal from scoring again in the
inning, throwing out Jose Vidro at the plate on Lee Stevens' fly
ball to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Payton and Benny Agbayani singled off reliever Steve Kline
(1-3) to lead off the Mets eighth. Melvin Mora sacrificed, and
McEwing hit a soft single to center.
Cubs 5, Phillies 4:
</P>
<P>
   At Chicago, Sammy Sosa tied the game with an eighth-inning homer
and Brant Brown won it in the ninth by scoring on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gant tied the game off Cubs closer Rick Aguilera with a
leadoff homer in the ninth. A few hours before the game, Cubs team
president Andy MacPhail accepted general manager Ed Lynch's
resignation.
Diamondbacks 4, Cardinals 3:
</P>
<P>
   At Phoenix, Erubiel Durazo hit a two-run double and the Arizona
bullpen pitched four scoreless innings to back up Armando Reynoso
(7-6).
</P>
<P>
   Greg Swindell pitched a perfect seventh and eighth. Matt Mantei
pitched the ninth for his first save since July 9.
Padres 4, Giants 3, 10 innings:
</P>
<P>
   At San Francisco, Ryan Klesko drove in three runs, including the
game-winner in the 10th inning off Alan Embree (1-3) against a
drawn-in infield.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds hit career home run No. 476 in the fourth, moving
into sole possession of 18th place on the all-time list, and ended
the game with a 410-foot fly ball that was caught at the wall in
right-center.
</P>
</TEXT>
