<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels Release Filipino  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Muslim rebels holding several
dozen hostages in the southern Philippines have released the
teen-age son of a soldier who was killed in a clash with the
rebels, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Richard Sintos, 17, was taken by helicopter from remote
Jolo island to Zamboanga, a commercial city in the southern
Philippines, Vice Governor Munib Estino said.
</P>
<P>
   Sintos' father died in a clash with the rebels on neighboring
Basilan island, and Sintos was seized afterward. It was unclear why
the teen was near the scene of the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the release, the Abu Sayyaf rebels are still holding
several groups of hostages, including teachers kidnapped from a
Basilan school and 19 mostly foreign hostages nabbed in April at a
Malaysian diving resort. They are believed to have 37 captives in
all -- six French, three Germans, two Finns, two South Africans,
seven Malaysians and 17 Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine negotiators are expecting the release of two of the
Basilan teachers and seven Malaysians from the diving resort after
agreeing with the rebels on a ransom amount, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The seven Malaysians were originally scheduled to be freed
Monday, but a last-minute rebel demand for a larger ransom blocked
the release: They asked for $337,500 per person, far more than the
$67,500 per person agreed upon earlier, negotiators said. On
Wednesday, the sides agreed on a revised figure somewhat higher
than the original amount.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the rebels released their first European captive, an
ailing German woman from among the diving resort group.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are demanding $1 million for each remaining European
hostage, negotiators say. The Philippine government has an official
no-ransom policy, but negotiators have confirmed that ransoms were
paid for two Malaysian hostages who were released earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf is the smaller of two main rebel groups fighting
for a separate Islamic nation for the Muslim minority in the
southern Philippines. The group has been accused of a wide range of
kidnappings and attacks on Christians in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators said Ghalib Andang, the Abu Sayyaf commander holding
most of the hostages, is no longer demanding an independent Muslim
nation as a condition for the hostages' release. But other rebel
commanders reportedly continue to demand such a state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 0231 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
