<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Wahid Shirks Criticism  </HEADLINE>
By SLOBODAN LEKIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's difficult transition to
democracy hit a new hurdle Thursday when the embattled president
defiantly shrugged off criticism from angry legislators, saying
they have no power to kick him out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to speculation that a group of lawmakers may try to
impeach him, President Abdurrahman Wahid said he had no intention
of being forced to quit before his five-year term ends in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ''According to the Constitution, the president ... cannot be
brought down or have action taken against him unless he commits
treason,'' he told the 500-member parliament.
</P>
<P>
   His comments appeared to raise the stakes in a continuing power
struggle between the legislative and executive branches, a central
problem in Indonesia's shift to democratic government. The
parliament, which for decades rubber-stamped former authoritarian
leader Suharto's decrees, has been flexing its muscles since it was
installed last year in multiparty elections.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid was summoned to parliament Thursday to answer allegations
that he wrongly fired two economic ministers in April.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech read by his state secretary, the president said the
dismissal of Trade and Industry Minister Yusuf Kalla and Investment
Minister Laksamana Sukardi was a political decision by the head of
state. He said that under Indonesia's system of government he was
under no obligation to explain his actions to the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   That comment was greeted with booing from the normally
respectful deputies in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's appearance was a prelude to a crucial Aug. 7 session
of the country's highest legislative body, the 700-member Peoples'
Consultative Assembly, during which Wahid is scheduled to deliver
his state-of-the-nation speech.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts have speculated that some Suharto backers and
Muslim hard-liners may try to impeach Wahid, citing a long-running
separatist war in the west, ongoing religious conflict in the east,
a poor economy and other unresolved problems.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid became Indonesia's first freely elected president in four
decades when he was chosen by the assembly last October. There were
high hopes that the respected Muslim leader would deliver sweeping
economic and political reforms to Indonesia after a generation of
dictatorial rule and rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wahid's unruly coalition government and unpredictable
administrative style have galvanized political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly's Aug. 7-18 meeting is expected to trigger protests
by student and human rights groups and about 100,000 political
supporters of various political parties. Authorities plan to deploy
more than 28,000 police, soldiers and civilian guards in the
capital for the session.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's parliamentary session, about 500 students
rallied in front of the building, demanding an end to the bloody
separatist war in western Aceh province and the Muslim-Christian
conflict in eastern Maluku province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
