<HEADLINE> American League Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By BEN WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Buehrle sure looked like he'd pitched more than one inning
in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first big league start, the 21-year-old lefty was in
command at the Metrodome as the Chicago White Sox beat Minnesota
3-2 on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was more nervous having lunch with my parents this afternoon
than I was on the mound,'' Buehrle said. ''Once the game started, I
felt fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Buehrle (1-0), promoted from Double-A Birmingham on Sunday, led
the White Sox to their fifth win in a row. He pitched seven
innings, giving up two runs and six hits.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a bit tired in the seventh and I began to rush my
pitches a bit,'' said Buehrle, toweling off after a beer shower
from his teammates. ''I never thought I could get a major league
win this quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   In other AL games, New York defeated Detroit 9-1, Texas held off
Anaheim 3-2, Seattle stopped Oakland 6-3, Toronto beat Tampa Bay
5-2, and Kansas City downed Cleveland 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   Brook Fordyce emerged from 1-for-18 slump with three hits,
including a home run as Chicago took a 3-0 lead after two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Getting some runs early certainly helped him,'' manager Jerry
Manuel said. ''But he had a good changeup and he was calm under
pressure. A rookie in his first start going seven solid innings is
more than a manager could have possibly hoped for.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He left the bases loaded twice tonight. That's a lot of poise
for a rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox increased their lead in the AL Central to 10&AMP;frac12;
games over Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins had a tough day in the health department.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Jay Canizaro was carried off the field with a
bruised lower leg after a collision with Tony Graffanino.
</P>
<P>
   Also, first base coach Jerry White was hit in the face by Matt
Lawton's helmet after the outfielder threw it down after a flyout.
White remained on the ground for a couple of minutes before being
helped to the bench, was forced to leave and wore a bandage on his
face after the game.
</P>
<P>
Yankees 9, Tigers 1
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens won his fourth straight start since coming off the
disabled list, leading New York over Detroit at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens moved into 35th place on the career win list with No.
255, moving ahead of Jack Morris and Hall of Famer Red Faber.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens struck out 11 and walked none, giving up six hits in
eight innings. It was his 96th career double-digit strikeout game,
fourth on the career list and one behind Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
Rangers 3, Angels 2
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Scarborough Green threw out Scott Spiezio at the
plate to end the game at Anaheim, stopping Texas' three-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio was on second base with two outs when Kevin Stocker
singled. Green, inserted for defensive purposes, fielded the ball
and threw on the fly to catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who made the tag.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio and Angels manager Mike Scioscia argued the call by
plate umpire Doug Eddings.
</P>
<P>
Royals 10, Indians 5
</P>
<P>
   Dave McCarty hit his first career grand slam and Johnny Damon
had a three-run homer as Kansas City beat Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Zaun also homered for the Royals, who won two in a row for
the first time since June 28-29. Jim Thome hit two home runs for
the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The 421st consecutive sellout crowd at Jacobs Field made the
Indians the first team to surpass 2 million in home attendance this
season.
</P>
<P>
Mariners 6, Athletics 3
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Moyer won his fourth straight start at the Oakland
Coliseum as Seattle defeated the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners closer Kazuhiro Sasaki struck out the side in the ninth
for his 23rd save. A's starter Kevin Appier is 0-4 in his last five
starts.
</P>
<P>
Blue Jays 5, Devil Rays 2
</P>
<P>
   Kelvim Escobar pitched two-hit ball for eight innings and
Toronto won at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Fullmer homered and drove in three runs. The Blue Jays have
homered in 18 straight games -- the major league record is 25 by
Atlanta (1998), Detroit (1994) and the Yankees (1941).
</P>
</TEXT>
