<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'West Wing' Among Emmy Contenders  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The White House is taking on the mob, with
the drama ''The West Wing'' and the gritty Mafia series ''The
Sopranos'' among the favorites for the 52nd Annual Primetime Emmy
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Contenders for the fall awards ceremony were to be announced
Thursday by Emmy winners Edie Falco (''The Sopranos'') and Michael
Badalucco (''The Practice'') at the Academy of Television Arts &AMP;
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Both ''The Sopranos'' and ''The West Wing'' were honored this
year with Peabody awards, which recognize television excellence,
while ''The West Wing'' received top awards last week from the
Television Critics Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Sopranos'' was the top nominee last year with 16 bids, but
the cable series about a suburban mobster lost the best drama prize
to ''The Practice.'' This year, ''The West Wing,'' a more
mainstream show about idealistic politicians, could fare better.
</P>
<P>
   Among comedy series, Emmy voters have the chance to rectify last
year's snub of ''Will &AMP; Grace,'' the sophomore sitcom about a gay
man-straight woman palship. A scrappy newcomer, ''Malcolm in the
Middle,'' may have an outside shot at a nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ally McBeal'' won the best comedy series award last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees will face a revised judging system. In a bid to
energize the awards, the academy is dispensing with blue-ribbon
voting panels that required a weekend spent viewing tapes at a
hotel and tended to draw older academy members.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, judges will be allowed to watch the nominated shows on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   The academy is experimenting with the approach in the top
categories that are part of the Emmy broadcast. Last year, the show
drew its lowest ratings since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ''You may see programs win that traditionally have been seen as
too avant garde or too edgy for the academy,'' said academy
President James B. Chabin. ''What we're trying to do is throw the
doors open and bring in a new generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sept. 10 awards ceremony will air on ABC with actor-comedian
Garry Shandling as host. Executive producer Don Mischer said the
show will emphasize comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.emmys.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
