<DOCNO> APW20000720.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 07:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reality TV Trend Disturbs Some  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- I have this queasy feeling about ''Survivor''
and ''Big Brother'' and it isn't because of something the
contestants ate.
</P>
<P>
   Let the islanders feast on grilled rat; not my problem as long
as Rodent-On-A-Bun doesn't pop up on menus.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not upset anymore by the fact that the shows, with
European pedigrees, veered dangerously close to un-American. The
dippy ''Big Brother'' and its dumb logo are annoyingly reminiscent
of a Mentos commercial, a bland, Eurogeneric type of ad designed
for international efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   In America's Manifest Destiny style, we have made the genre our
own, pitting young against old, men against women, black against
white.
</P>
<P>
   What really disturbs me is that these so-called reality shows
imperil the dramas and comedies that make TV a magic box.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know, television's a big tent for a big country, with
room for wrestling, game shows and, maybe, Laura Schlessinger. TV's
roots lie not only in the esteemed ''Playhouse 90,'' but in ''Queen
for a Day,'' that midcentury marvel in which tragic housewives wept
for prizes.
</P>
<P>
   But with viewers entranced by ''Survivor'' shenanigans and
network executives bewitched by the ratings, it's difficult not to
fret.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasters are battling for survival in a gazillion-channel
world, and anything goes. Why should ABC stick with low-rated
''Sports Night'' when it can clone Regis and another
''Millionaire'' for instant gratification?
</P>
<P>
   ''Do I hope the trend goes away in a hurry? Sure,'' said Aaron
Sorkin, creator of ''The West Wing'' and ''Sports Night'' and one
of the wizards of TV fiction. ''There isn't a writer writing that
thing ('Survivor'), so who wants it on television?''
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin's acclaimed White House drama has a home at NBC, where
programming executives are wearing sackcloth and ashes for failing
to capitalize on the reality trend.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are network heads who are getting jumped up and down on
right now for not getting on the reality bandwagon,'' Sorkin told
reporters recently. ''I wish they were being applauded instead.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, NBC has assembled a crisis team to review the literally
hundreds of reality pitches pouring in and find the real cubic
zirconia among them.
</P>
<P>
   One leading candidate: ''Chains of Love'' (based on a European
program, natch), in which a woman is bound to four men who will be
discarded one by one until only her Prince Charming, or something
reasonably close, remains.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to abandon what I think is the hallmark of our
network -- quality dramas and sitcoms -- but we can't ignore this
(reality trend) as something that may go away a year from now or
two years from now,'' NBC West Coast President Scott Sassa said
this week.
</P>
<P>
   How reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, dizzy with the continued success of ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' is stalking more nonfiction shows.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Chase'' is one, a brainchild of Matt Damon and Ben Affleck
that asks viewers to track down a player let loose somewhere in the
country. Sounds like the Oscar-winning pair (''Good Will Hunting'')
saves their best work for the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Fox, with painful memories of ''Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?'' receding, it's full steam ahead. Possible new
shows include ''I Want a Divorce,'' in which couples saying ''I
don't anymore'' compete for community property.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, for its part, is already planning another ''Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   If reality shows were confined to the rerun season, that would
be OK. But ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' roared out of summer
1999 and now occupies a hefty chunk of ABC's primetime real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Imitation is the sincerest form of television, the late satirist
Fred Allen observed, so it's not farfetched to worry about reality
growing to frightening proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, dazzled by tribal warfare on ''Survivor'' and by ''Big
Brother'' contestant Karen dissing her absent spouse, viewers can
be distracted from the pleasures of well-told stories.
</P>
<P>
   But what do you really want to pull out of your TV memory bank:
a snapshot of Karen whining, or one of George Clooney sweeping
Julianna Margulies off her feet for keeps on ''ER''?
</P>
<P>
   And take a moment to appreciate what goes into the making of
reality vs. fiction. While the geniuses at ''Chains of Love''
debate chain length, Sorkin is orchestrating a new ''West Wing''
season that will riff on civil liberties, gun violence and the
inner lives of its fascinating characters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people want something good to chew on,'' Robin Green,
an executive producer on ''The Sopranos,'' said during a recent
tribute to the brilliant HBO mob drama.
</P>
<P>
   Bet she doesn't mean charred rat.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   MORE 'LAW': Stephanie March, recently on Broadway in ''Death of
a Salesman,'' will join the cast of ''Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims
Unit'' this fall. She'll play a dedicated district attorney as part
of an effort to beef up the ''Law'' part of the NBC series that
stars Christopher Meloni and Mariska Hargitay as police detectives.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
