<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 87; Nasdaq Climbs 60  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks surged higher in early trading Thursday
as investors poured back into the markets seeking bargains after
two days of losses.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 87.68 at 10,783.76.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 4.87 at 1,486.83, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 60.63 at 4,116.26.
</P>
<P>
   Bellwether technology company IBM reported better-than-expected
earnings after the market closed Wednesday. Investors flocked to
the stock, pushing it up $10.032, or 10 percent, to $114.188 in
morning trading.
</P>
<P>
   The move was significant because Wednesday's selloff, which saw
the Nasdaq Stock Market lose 122 points and the Dow Jones
industrial average fall 44 points, was spurred by disappointed
investors who sold the shares of tech companies that didn't live up
to high earnings expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Some bargain hunting was expected in early trading Thursday. But
the mood could change depending on the words of Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Alan Greenspan, who is testifying before a Senate
committee this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Investors across both the stock and bond markets have been
anxiously awaiting Greenspan's testimony, hoping the chairman will
give some hint as to the future direction of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 136.90 million
shares, up from Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 3.70 at 531.56.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan markets were closed for the holidays. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.16 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.31 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
up 0.93 percent.
</P>
