<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon-U.N. Team Inspect Border  </HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHIAM, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanese and U.N. officers flew by
helicopter and drove through rough terrain along the
Lebanese-Israeli frontier Thursday in the final stages of verifying
the Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The team flew by U.N. helicopter from the headquarters of the
United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon in the border town of
Naqoura on the Mediterranean coast to Mount Hermon in the east. The
one-hour flight covered the so-called blue line, the border drawn
by U.N. cartographers last month for the purpose of confirming the
Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese and U.N. officers began the final border inspection
Monday after U.N. Middle East envoy Terje Roed-Larsen informed
Lebanese leaders that Israel had made significant efforts to end
its frontier violations.
</P>
<P>
   Work had been expected to be over by Wednesday, but difficult
terrain and landmines has delayed the process. It was not clear
whether the task would be completed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese acceptance of the completion of the May 24 Israeli
withdrawal, already verified by the United Nations, would pave the
way for deployment of U.N. peacekeepers and then the Lebanese army
into an area controlled by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were upbeat about the progress so far.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going very well,'' Brig. Gen. Jim Sreenan, the Irish
deputy UNIFIL commander, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything is going on smoothly,'' said Brig. Gen. Amin
Hoteit, head of the Lebanese team.
</P>
<P>
   The team later set out by four-wheel-drive vehicles from the
helicopter landing zone in Khiam, a six kilometers (four miles)
north of the Israeli border, and headed toward the village of
Ghajar on the corner of Lebanon and the Israeli-occupied Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of Ghajar was awarded to Lebanon under the blue
line demarcation, which was based on 1923 maps from the French and
British colonial eras. The village's Arab residents have been
protesting the division of their community.
</P>
<P>
   The team stopped outside but did not enter the village, where
hundreds of men, women and children gathered on the fence shouting
across a valley.
</P>
<P>
   Hoteit looked through binoculars toward the village.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters saw no sign of the Israeli soldiers and the military
outposts that had been guarding the area in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hoteit said three-fifths of the village was awarded to Lebanon
and two-fifths to Syria, in part of the Golan Heights occupied by
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Israeli army officials said a compromise between
Israel and the United Nations was reached under which Israeli
troops would not circulate in the Lebanese part of the village, but
villagers could move freely from one side of the village to the
other.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese and U.N. officers then moved to an area across from
the Israeli town of Metulla, where another Israeli violation
appeared to have been rectified. The Israelis had cut down scores
of wild trees before moving back the fence about 100 meters
(yards).
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the Metulla area, about a dozen Lebanese
refugees stood at the fence, watching the team work. They were
among nearly 7,000 mostly pro-Israeli Lebanese who have fled to
Israel just before the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Nancy Soderberg, the deputy U.S. ambassador at the
United Nations who was visiting Beirut, anticipated ''in the next
few days, a clean bill of health on the blue line that would
trigger an immediate deployment of both UNIFIL and government
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Beirut has said it will not consider sending its security forces
to the areas vacated by Israel at least until Israel ends border
encroachments.
</P>
<P>
   Another 1,000 soldiers were expected to join the 4,500-member
UNIFIL. The bulk of Ukraine's 540-member contingent was arriving
Thursday in Lebanon. A passenger jet brought 144 soldiers to
Beirut. Another 111 soldiers along with 339 transport trucks,
military vehicles and four mine-clearing vehicles arrived by sea.
</P>
<P>
   sfg-hd/sjs
</P>
</TEXT>
