<BODY>
<HEADLINE> H. Kong Rail Line Threatens Birds  </HEADLINE>
By MARGARET WONG
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Ng So-kwan gets up every morning at 1 a.m. and
works until 7 a.m., harvesting spinach on one of Hong Kong's few
remaining farms. She enjoys the last two hours most, when she is
calmed by chattering birds -- a little egret or a Chinese pond heron
sweeping past before perching on a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love hearing the birds sing,'' Ng says. ''The music is so
harmonic and soothing.''
</P>
<P>
   This may be the last season she hears so many birds.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the government-owned Kowloon-Canton Railway Corp.
are planning to lay a new rail line through part of Long Valley,
the largest remaining freshwater wetland in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The low-lying wetland is home to more than 210 species of birds,
including four that are globally threatened -- the greater spotted
eagle, the imperial eagle, the Japanese yellow bunting and Pallas'
grasshopper warbler.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the only breeding ground in Hong Kong for the rare
painted snipe, a chicken-sized bird with long bill, short legs and
colorful facial markings. Only about 20 or 30 are believed to be
living in the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials hope the new railway will help cut back on
the heavy automobile traffic that is shrouding Hong Kong in fumes
as more people move to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   While environmentalists welcome the pollution-free railway as
the best cure to Hong Kong's traffic woes, they insist it should be
rerouted away from Long Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The 4.6-mile passenger rail, elevated on a viaduct for 1.2 miles
across Long Valley, will branch out from the existing railway
between Hong Kong and mainland China and connect to a new border
terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Railroad officials maintain it is the only feasible route -- and
with transportation worries outweighing environmental concerns in
Hong Kong, government approval of the plan seems likely.
</P>
<P>
   Bird lovers aren't pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the best place to get to know birds,'' says lawyer and
avid bird watcher Paul Harris, who says he can spot up to 50
species in one afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Long Valley, just south of the border from a mainland Chinese
industrial zone, is the only remaining freshwater stopover in Hong
Kong for many birds during the annual migration, usually between
October and April, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very important for them to take a break as they won't
have energy to fly so far,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If they land in mainland China, they face an additional peril:
People kill them for food.
</P>
<P>
   Long Valley is recognized as a globally important site for the
preservation of avian diversity by BirdLife International, a
conservation partnership of organizations in more than 100
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Its fields are often crowded with bird watchers during migratory
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say the railway is urgently needed to cope
with the double-digit annual growth of passenger traffic between
Hong Kong and the mainland, which has accelerated since Hong Kong
reverted from British to Chinese sovereignty in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The number of border crossings has increased 17 percent annually
over the last three years to 77.2 million in 1999, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   And Hong Kong's population is growing fast, with many people
moving into northern areas closer to the border.
</P>
<P>
   Long Valley residents complain of being left in the dark about
the railroad plans that will disrupt their way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government and the railway company have never talked to
us,'' said Ng, the vegetable farmer.
</P>
<P>
   James Blake, senior director for capital projects at the railway
company, defended the Long Valley rail project, saying officials
plan to compensate for the loss of wetland by creating an elongated
manmade wetland after the construction ends.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists and bird lovers say there is no evidence
the birds will be able to thrive on the planned sausage-shaped
wetland.
</P>
<P>
   ''The birds are not like flowers that can be replanted
elsewhere,'' Harris says. ''Once they've left when the construction
starts, they won't come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 1459 </TRAILER>
