<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Gets Reprieve With New Talks  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN NOVECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- It wasn't just the Camp David summit that was
granted a sudden midnight reprieve. Ehud Barak got one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, the Israeli leader faces a decidedly bleak landscape:
his coalition government in tatters, a parliament battle looming
that could topple him, and the potential for a new cycle of violent
conflict with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens in the coming days at Camp David, no one
thinks Barak's domestic problems will melt away. But his best
chance to surmount them -- and make his reprieve more lasting -- is
to somehow bring home a peace deal that will silence his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Those critics were out in force Thursday. Even as his supporters
expressed relief that the talks were back on, the prime minister
was assailed by right-wing Israelis for making too many
concessions, and by Palestinians for making too few.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition Likud leader Ariel Sharon said Barak had broken
promises to his people and created a ''dangerous precedent'' by
setting up ''an impossible starting point'' for later negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   And Palestinian minister Ziad Abu Zayyad said Barak's ''stubborn
position is a call for another war.'' Referring specifically to the
tinderbox issue of Jerusalem, he called the Israeli stance ''a
tempting invitation to all fanatics and suicide bombers.''
</P>
<P>
   A Barak ally, Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh, countered
that Israel ''has gone out of its way to display flexibility. Now
it's the turn of the Palestinians. That's what we are expecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak was already badly weakened when he left Israel 10 days
ago. A day earlier he'd lost his parliamentary majority when three
right-wing parties deserted him. Then he barely survived a
humiliating no-confidence vote while his plane to Washington idled
on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   His troubles didn't stop once he left: more than 100,000
right-wing protesters jammed into a Tel Aviv square on a Sunday
night, declaring they wouldn't accept broad concessions to the
Palestinians. ''Barak is dangerous to Jews,'' one banner read.
</P>
<P>
   And though a later no-confidence vote fizzled because Barak was
out of town, he faces another political land mine in the beginning
of August: a vote on a bill calling for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the political arena, things looked dire as well. Army
officials have said they're bracing for a possible upswing in
violence in the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
   Hanan Ashrawi, a frequent spokeswoman for the Palestinians,
warned there would be ''a situation of tremendous volatility and
conflict'' if the summit failed. Both sides feared what the other
might do: the Palestinians might declare an independent state
unilaterally; the Israelis might respond by annexing parts of the
Palestinian lands.
</P>
<P>
   When Barak left Israel, some analysts felt his best chance --
maybe his only chance -- was to come back from Camp David with a
solid deal that would finally give Israelis a true taste of peace.
Then, they said, he could go to the public with the plan and
reclaim his mandate.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, it doesn't seem to be turning out that way.
</P>
<P>
   After nine days of hard talks, Barak, who left Israel with such
a sense of historic purpose, felt compelled to write a letter to
Clinton accusing the Palestinians of negotiating in bad faith. The
Palestinians said Barak was the intransigent one.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with talks extended at least for a few days, Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat have another chance to reverse the
tide. But all sides -- Israelis, Palestinians and Americans -- warn
the gaps remain very wide, and the chances of bridging them very
small.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't succeed, Arafat can tell his people he didn't
abandon their dream of east Jerusalem as sovereign capital of their
independent state, or of the right of millions of refugees to
return home. Barak, too, could say he at least stuck to the
principles he promised he wouldn't violate, and didn't bargain away
the dreams of his people.
</P>
<P>
   But judging from the downbeat assessments in the Israeli press
Thursday, Barak would have a tougher time of it.
</P>
<P>
   Having wagered his career on the single mission of peacemaking,
commentators implied, he would look like the emperor with no
clothes. Columnist Nahum Barnea said Barak's precarious political
standing was not even his biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most importantly, he has no clear agenda as a leader that will
allow him to retain the backing of the public,'' he wrote in Yediot
Ahronot.
</P>
<P>
   ''More than the left's criticism of his intransigence, and the
right's of his concessions, he should fear the vacuum, the feeling
that everything is falling apart around him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
