<HEADLINE> Cabot Prizes honor Latin American coverage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Four journalists, including The Associated Press
bureau chief for Mexico and Central America, will be honored for
excellence in reporting on Latin America, Columbia University said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Francisco Santos, a columnist for the Colombian
newspaper El Tiempo who lives in exile, is to receive a special
citation, Columbia said in announcing the 2000 Maria Moors Cabot
Prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Winners of the awards for outstanding coverage of Latin America
and the Caribbean are: Eloy O. Aguilar, AP bureau chief for Mexico
and Central America; Paul Knox, international affairs reporter for
The Globe and Mail of Toronto; Ricardo Uceda, chief of the
investigative unit at El Comercio, of Lima, Peru; and Lloyd
Williams, senior associate editor of the Gleaner newspapers of
Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabot awards, in their 62nd year, honor reporters and
editors who have ''demonstrated compassion and commitment to
freedom of the press and inter-American understanding,'' Columbia
said in a statement. They are administered by the university's
Graduate School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar has been chief of the AP bureau in Mexico City since
1979, coordinating news and photo coverage of Mexico and Central
America. He has overseen coverage of wars in Guatemala, El Salvador
and Nicaragua and helped establish the AP's bureau in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Knox has written and edited for The Globe and Mail since 1978,
and is also a Spanish-language commentator for Radio Canada
International. He has reported from all over Latin America and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Uceda, of El Comercio, has worked on investigations into alleged
election fraud, the disappearance and murder of a teacher and nine
students, and surgical sterilizations performed on pregnant women
without their knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who began his career in 1960 as a trainee at the Daily
Gleaner, is now senior associate editor of the Gleaner Publications
group. He recently wrote a series about Colombian drug traffickers
moving into Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   Santos was to receive a special citation for his columns in El
Tiempo, in which he has denounced kidnaping and massacres. He
survived a kidnaping a decade ago, and fled Colombia after writing
against guerrilla violence.
</P>
<P>
   The awards are to be presented Sept. 27 in a ceremony on
Columbia's Manhattan campus.
</P>
</TEXT>
