<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troopers, governor say factions and infighting common in State Police ranks </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Factions vying for support and favor have
always competed within the ranks of the State Police, insiders say.
</P>
<P>
   The difference now is that the infighting, the accusations and
the rancor are becoming widely public. From lawsuits to e-mail
newsgroups, troopers are criticizing everyone from the governor to
the superintendent to fellow officers.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers said the first public charges of racial profiling
started the rumblings. The widely publicized April 1998 shooting on
the New Jersey Turnpike, the state's admission that troopers
targeted minority drivers and the firing of Col. Carl Williams each
ratcheted up the tension, troopers contend.
</P>
<P>
   The latest flashpoint: that picture of Gov. Christie Whitman
searching a black drug suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Even Whitman, who points to disgruntled troopers for the release
of that photograph, admits the infighting is damaging efforts to
reform the State Police. The governor, whose term ends in January
2002, said she fears Superintendent Carson Dunbar will not return
to head the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''My concern is that once I'm no longer governor he is no longer
there,'' Whitman said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a very strong faction that wants him out of there. A
very strong faction that says we're going to be here after you're
gone so we're not going to change,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   That entrenchment has divided ranks, splitting troopers along
racial lines, some minority officers said. Whites avoid blacks and
Hispanics and some white officers are shunned because they support
Dunbar's reform agenda, said one minority trooper who spoke on
condition that his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know some troopers who are afraid to ride with other
troopers,'' the veteran patrol officer said. ''It comes down to
'Are you with us or are you against us?' That's the mentality many
troopers have.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, Dunbar declined to be interviewed about
trooper morale.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers themselves are speaking.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, 40 troopers had named the state and the State
Police in lawsuits, many alleging they were subjected to
discrimination and harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Some troopers apparently are venting their ire on an Internet
newsletter dubbed ''Troop Rumblings''. Messages, often anonymous,
use sarcastic nicknames to refer to Dunbar and Whitman. Many of the
e-mail messages directly criticize State Police work schedules,
admissions about racial profiling and minority hiring practices.
</P>
<P>
   Many troopers are angry, but they are not fighting among
themselves, said David Jones, vice president of the State Troopers
Fraternal Association of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The real target is the Whitman administration, Jones said.
Troopers are disgusted because the attorney general's office
admitted that officers engaged in racial profiling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The message from the top clearly is disappointment and disgust
with what has happened to us. In the name of political correctness,
political agendas, we were thrown under a bus,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Any talk that white troopers alienate minorities comes only from
a handful of black and Hispanic troopers, and they have filed
lawsuits, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're talking about a dozen individuals who have been crying
from day one. They don't speak for the rank-and-file minorities,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean the troopers do not have factions -
groups of officers with some common agenda, he said. In decades
past, as each colonel took control, his allies were elevated into
key positions, Jones said. Troopers will align themselves to
officers seen as likely candidates for top jobs, Jones explained.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the factions. But it's always been like that. It's
nothing unusual,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-20-00 1539 </TRAILER>
