<HEADLINE> Feds To Ivestigate W. Va. Killing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department announced Thursday it
is opening a preliminary investigation into the death of a gay
black man who was murdered in Marion County, W.Va. The FBI began
the inquiry hours after a meeting between the victim's parents and
the department's No. 2 official.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur ''J.R.'' Warren, 26, of Grant Town, W.Va., was beaten to
death July 4 and then run over by a car to make it look like a
hit-and-run accident.
</P>
<P>
   Two 17-year-old white cousins are charged with the slaying in
what civil rights and gay rights leaders and Warren's family regard
as a hate crime motivated by the fact that the victim was gay and
African American.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Department of Justice, Civil Rights Division, in
coordination with the Federal Bureau of Investigation and the U.S.
Attorney's Office in Wheeling (W.Va.) has opened a preliminary
investigation into this incident,'' Deputy Attorney General Eric
Holder said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Holder said his conversation with the victim's parents ''was an
informative, disturbing and emotional meeting about a senseless and
brutal killing. ... We will continue to work cooperatively with
local authorities in this matter to determine what if any
additional federal action is warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh, FBI spokesman Jeff Killeen said the preliminary
inquiry will ''determine if the victim's federal civil rights were
violated'' and that the inquiry ''is based upon additional
information recently brought to the FBI's attention.'' The
Pittsburgh FBI office covers West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Rights groups and Warren's relatives are concerned that the two
17-year-olds charged with the killing may be tried as juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   If tried as juveniles by local authorities in West Virginia,
David Parker and Jared Wilson ''could walk out of prison in three
years,'' said David Smith of the Human Rights Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important that the FBI is involved,'' Hilary Shelton of
the Washington branch of the NAACP said after meeting with Holder,
other Justice Department officials and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a racially motivated hate crime,'' said Wade
Henderson, director of the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's mother, Brenda Warren, expressed frustration with
the Marion County sheriff's department, which is investigating the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot see how they can say hate was not involved,'' said
Mrs. Warren. ''This should never have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's department has not officially released a motive in
the slaying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
