<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Ends Assad Mourning Period  </HEADLINE>
By ALBERT AJI
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Syria's 40-day mourning period for
President Hafez Assad ended Thursday with tributes in his hometown
of Qardaha from Arab officials and some who served under him during
his three decades in power.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's 34-year-old son and successor, Bashar, sat surrounded by
aides, listening in the front row of a meeting hall to about two
dozen speakers during the 5&AMP;frac12;-hour ceremony in Qardaha, 210 miles
northwest of Damascus. The only relative to speak at the gathering
of more than 1,000 people was Hafez Assad's older brother Jamil,
who briefly thanked Syrians for their condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Abdel-Halim Khaddam, in a ceremony closed to many
journalists but carried live on Syrian television, said he knew the
late Assad as a president, a leader and a political thinker.
Khaddam, a vice president since 1984, described him as a man who
''kept in his steadfastness until his departure.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Hafez Assad's insistence that Israel return to
Syria the entire Golan Heights captured during the 1967 Mideast
war, Khaddam said: ''They could not bring him down to cede or
relinquish or compromise on any right related to home territory.''
Bashar Assad, who was sworn in as president Monday, has said he
will follow his father's course in negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Arab unity was the elder Assad's preoccupation to his final
days, Khaddam said. ''He was confident that Arabs' future is in
their unity, that their security, stability and renaissance rests
in their solidarity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Mustafa Tlass spoke of the years in which he
accompanied the elder Assad: ''I fought with him, shared with him
every rebellion, insurgence, coup or revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Hafez Assad gave his position as defense minister to Tlass when
Assad took power in a bloodless 1970 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Among others to address the gathering were Nabih Berri, speaker
of the Lebanese Parliament, and Hezbollah leader Sheik Hassan
Nasrallah. Syria holds sway over Lebanese politics and is
influential over the Hezbollah guerrilla group that fought Israel
during its lengthy occupation of southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Hafez Assad died June 10 at age 69 and was buried in Qardaha
next to his eldest son Basil, who died in a car accident in 1994.
Thursday's event was held in a hall put up to accommodate mourners
who attended Basil's funeral six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   No events marking the end of the mourning period were held in
Damascus. Though black flags still were hanging Thursday night from
some street lights and private homes and businesses in the capital,
they will likely come down in the next day or two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
