<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Judge Releases Serb  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT H. REID
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a move to ease
tensions, an ethnic Albanian judge Thursday released a Serb whose
detention led to rioting and mass street protests in the largest
Serb community remaining in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Dalibor Vukovic, 24, was freed without bail until a further
hearing is held within two weeks. He was charged with arson, theft
and assault in the burning of an ethnic Albanian's car last month.
</P>
<P>
   His arrest Monday night outraged the Serb community in Kosovka
Mitrovica, which attacked U.N. police, forcing the United Nations
to suspend police operations for a while. Serb leaders said the
offense was minor compared to unsolved killings and attacks against
Serbs by ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Vukovic, a medical student, is one of several Serb militants who
watch over the main bridge leading from the ethnic
Albanian-dominated south bank of the Ibar River.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally hours after Vukovic was freed, Serb leader Oliver
Ivanovic told about 1,000 people that the Serbian community's
response to the arrest ''proved that we can fight for justice in a
civilized manner.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We will act in the same way to any undemocratic decision by
the international community,'' Ivanovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Vukovic told the crowd: ''As long as you were here, I knew was
not alone.''
</P>
<P>
   During a hearing in the dingy district court building, located
in a heavily guarded U.N. compound, Vukovic told the judge that he
had been drinking that night and could not remember the attack,
according to U.N. spokesman Mike Keats.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were not allowed in the courtroom, but Keats said
Vukovic expressed regret that the incident had happened.
</P>
<P>
   By releasing Vukovic but still keeping the case active, the
United Nations found a way to defuse the crisis while still
following legal procedures. William Nash, the U.N. administrator
for the city, said he was pleased with the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is essential that the rule of law prevails in north
Mitrovica and that all attempts to interfere with it are
thwarted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome also bolstered the position of Ivanovic. Serb
sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Ivanovic was
under pressure from Serb extremists to push the arrest issue into
open confrontation with the United Nations and the NATO-led Kosovo
Force.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the crisis underscored the deep divisions between ethnic
Albanians and Serbs as well as the tenuous nature of U.N. control
in this Serb-dominated area. U.N. police officers were attacked and
some of their apartments ransacked.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. police commander for the area, Canadian Beloit
Belanger, said U.N. police had lost several weapons during the four
days of turmoil. Computers were stolen from the U.N. police station
in the nearby Serb town of Zvecan, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians consider the ethnic division of the city as a
symbol of the failure of the United Nations and NATO to build a
united Kosovo. The handling of the Vukovic case is likely to be
seen by many ethnic Albanians as another example of the
international mission knuckling under to Serb pressure.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, an ethnic Albanian leader who was a member of the
delegation that tried to negotiate an end to the Kosovo crisis in
Rambouillet, France, last year complained that the United Nations
had allowed a parallel, Serb administration to develop in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Blerim Shala, writing in the Albanian language newspaper Zeri,
said the new Serb governmental structure ''does not accept U.N.
jurisdiction on the other side of the river.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 1605 </TRAILER>
