<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon: U.S. Troops Supported  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite a recent upswing in anti-American
protests, the governments and majority of people in South Korea and
Japan still support keeping U.S. troops on their soil, the Pentagon
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have always been pockets of resistance,'' Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth Bacon said. ''And I think that that's what we're
seeing in these two countries, that the pockets, the resisters, are
episodically more energetic sometimes than they are at other
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question about why U.S. commanders had increased
security this week among troops in South Korea, Bacon said it
followed last month's stabbing death of an Army doctor in Seoul's
Itaewon shopping district, recent demonstrations against Americans
and an attack against the wives of two American servicemen, also in
a shopping area.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, tens of thousands of protesters formed a chain around
a major U.S. air base Thursday at Okinawa, in a show of opposition
to the American military presence ahead of President Clinton's
visit for this weekend's Group of Eight summit. It followed a
demonstration by thousands last week in which Okinawans protested
U.S. presence and criticized recent alleged crimes by American
servicemen on Japan's southern island.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at the Pentagon's regular briefing it the events
represented growing anti-American sentiment in the Pacific, Bacon
said: ''I don't think I see anything particularly new in the
Pacific.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that we have a situation where the governments of
South Korea and the government of Japan and the vast majority of
the people support our security presence there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there has been ''perhaps a little spike'' in activity by
opponents because of the G-8 summit and recent political
developments in South Korea. He was referring to last month's
North-South summit that somewhat warmed relations between the two
Koreas and led to the question of how much longer 37,000 U.S.
troops might be needed there to help keep peace on the long divided
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the U.S. military imposed strict limits on drinking
and a late-night curfew on service members, hoping to defuse
tensions before Clinton's arrival. About 47,000 U.S. military
service people are stationed in Japan, nearly two-thirds of them in
Okinawa, 1,000 miles southwest of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   In Korea, U.S. commanders this week extended patrols by military
police in major night spots in Seoul that are frequented by
American soldiers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 1606 </TRAILER>
