<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York jobless rate down slightly in June  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York state's June unemployment rate of
4.5 percent slipped slightly from the rate of 4.6 percent the
previous month, state labor officials reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The figure was higher than the June national unemployment rate
of 4 percent but improved over the state's June 1999 jobless rate
of 5.3 percent, the state Labor Department reported.
</P>
<P>
   There were 7,156,300 private-sector jobs in New York during
June, the highest in state history, officials said. The state
gained 159,900 private-sector jobs between June 1999 and June 2000.
The 2.3 percent job growth gain was slightly ahead of the national
rate of 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among individual counties, Albany and Warren (2.5 percent each)
and Putnam (2.6 percent) had the lowest jobless rates last month
while St. Lawrence (7.1 percent) and the Bronx (6.7 percent) had
the highest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The state's jobless figures are based on monthly surveys of
18,000 business establishments. The jobs are both full- and
part-time. The jobs data does not include agricultural workers, the
self-employed and domestic workers in private households.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide jobless figures are seasonally adjusted, which
means they are altered to take into account normal fluctuations in
employment - schools being out of session, for instance, or summer
tourism-related jobs - over the course of a year.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a breakdown of seasonally unadjusted figures for major
metropolitan areas in the state:
</P>
<P>
   -New York City, 186,800 jobless or 5.4 percent in June, compared
with 5.7 percent in May and 6.5 percent in June of last year.
</P>
<P>
   -Albany area, 13,800 or 3.0 percent, compared with 3.1 percent
and 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   -Binghamton area, 3,700 or 2.9 percent, compared with 2.9 and
4.0.
</P>
<P>
   -Buffalo area, 28,700 or 5.0 percent, compared with 4.4 and 5.4.
</P>
<P>
   -Elmira area, 2,300 or 5.0 percent, compared with 4.7 and 4.8.
</P>
<P>
   -Poughkeepsie area, 3,600 or 2.9 percent, compared with 2.9 and
3.3.
</P>
<P>
   -Rochester area, 22,000 or 3.7 percent, compared with 3.8 and
4.1.
</P>
<P>
   -Syracuse area, 13,900 or 3.7 percent, compared with 3.8 and
4.1.
</P>
<P>
   -Utica-Rome area, 5,600 or 3.8 percent, compared with 3.6 and
4.1.
</P>
<P>
   -Nassau County, 20,900 or 2.9 percent, compared with 2.5 and
3.2.
</P>
<P>
   -Suffolk County, 22,400 or 3.0 percent, compared with 2.7 and
3.7.
</P>
<P>
   -Westchester County, 14,200 or 3.1 percent, compared with 2.7
and 3.6.
</P>
<P>
   -Rockland County, 5,000 or 3.3 percent, compared with 2.8 and
3.8.
</P>
<P>
   -Putnam County, 1,500 or 2.6 percent, compared with 2.2 and
3.3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
