<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor vetoes bill allowing schools special services aid  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki on Thursday vetoed a bill
that would have allowed school districts outside New York's five
largest cities to receive special services aid if they chose not to
join local BOCES.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said the state would have to spend $7.5 million each year
to provide the funding for special services aid to such school
districts. That amount was not included in the $13.6 billion set
aside for public school aid in the 2000-01 state budget or in other
multi-year financial plans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said ''any decision to modify a particular aid
formula should be made in the context of the budgetary process.''
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, all school districts other than those in the
''Big 5'' - New York City, Yonkers, Buffalo, Syracuse and Rochester
- are eligible to become members of their local boards of
cooperative educational services. BOCES members share support
services ranging from technical and occupational training classes
to making sure eligible children are receiving social service
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Big 5 school districts don't qualify for BOCES membership but
instead receive special services aid for programs similar to what a
BOCES would normally provide.
</P>
<P>
   The failed legislation would have made seven non-Big 5 school
districts that are currently not members of BOCES eligible for
special services aid. The districts are: Albany, Troy, Hoosick
Falls, Lackawanna, Newburgh, Amsterdam and Mamaroneck.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Palmer, superintendent of the Albany city school
district, said Pataki's veto was a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ''We bear the entire burden of the entire cost of the program.
We get no aid,'' Palmer said. ''I thought this might help us with
good financial underpinning.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the district had considered joining the local BOCES but
decided against it for financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd be spending more and we'd potentially lose control of
some of the great programs and teachers that we've got in place,''
Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Albany district currently buys some things such as computer
services from local BOCES, but Palmer said it doesn't receive any
state aid because it's not a member. If the district joins a BOCES,
it would become a member of a council of about 20 districts and
would no longer exercise independent control, he added.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman John McEneny, a co-sponsor of the bill, said
the legislation would have ''restored some equity to the system.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it made very good sense,'' the Albany Democrat said
of the bill. ''(Pataki) should be bold enough to level the playing
field for vocational education.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill has passed in the state Assembly in past years, but
this was the first year that the state Senate also gave its
approval. Assemblyman Ronald Canestrari, an Albany County Democrat,
said he had been ''very optimistic'' that Pataki would sign the
bill and was ''very disappointed'' when that didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Canestrari said the state could have found a way to allocate the
money required for the special services aid out of its $77.5
billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure there's flexibility in the budget to correct this
inequity,'' Canestrari said. ''Many bills have appropriations that
are not in the budget. I don't find (Pataki's argument)
persuasive.''
</P>
<P>
   In other bills acted on by Pataki:
</P>
<P>
   -A package of legislation allows Nassau County to impose a tax
of up to 3 percent on all hotel and motel rooms until Dec. 31,
2005. The measure approved by Pataki also sets an entertainment
ticket surcharge of $1.50 in the county and allows the county
police department to charge fees for accident reports. The county
is trying to work its way out of serious budget problems.
</P>
<P>
   -The number of family court judges in Monroe County will be
increased from five to six.
</P>
<P>
   -A bill that would have eliminated the additional 5.35 percent
employee contribution for New York City sanitation workers who
participated in a 20-year retirement program was vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, sanitation workers who participate in the
program are required to make the contributions through 30 years of
service. Pataki said reducing that period to 20 years would cost
the city an additional $1.2 million, which would violate the
original agreement between the city and unions that the program did
not impose additional costs on the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
