<HEADLINE> Marchand Nominated for Fifth Emmy  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA WERNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A month after her death, Nancy Marchand was
nominated for another Emmy on Thursday for her career-capping role
as the scheming mob matriarch Livia in ''The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchand won four consecutive Emmys from 1979 to 1982 for her
role as the proper publisher Margaret Pynchon on ''Lou Grant.'' She
died of lung cancer June 18, a day before her 72nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Marchand was also nominated last year for ''The Sopranos'' and
didn't win, though she did take home a Golden Globe award earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   She will join Michael J. Fox as sentimental favorites at the
awards show in September. Fox was nominated for lead comedy actor
for his role in ''Spin City.'' Afflicted with Parkinson's disease,
the 39-year-old star left the ABC series after the season finale in
May.
</P>
<P>
   While sentiment is on Marchand's side, the Emmys actually have
an uneven history when it comes to handing out awards posthumously,
said Thomas O'Neil, an awards show analyst.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the year after he died of stroke complications, Raul
Julia won an Emmy for lead actor in a miniseries or special for his
performance as murdered rain forest activist Chico Mendes in HBO's
''The Burning Season.''
</P>
<P>
   But Phil Hartman of ''NewsRadio'' was nominated in 1998 after he
was shot to death by his wife. He was considered a favorite, but
lost in the supporting comedy actor category to David Hyde Pierce
of ''Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   James Gandolfini, as Tony Soprano, is the star of ''The
Sopranos,'' but Marchand's scenes were among the most compelling.
The relationship between Tony and his sullen, self-pitying mother
provided much of the critically acclaimed show's emotional
backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Producers of the HBO series had envisioned Livia for just a
handful of episodes, but her character proved so popular that the
role was expanded. Rather than try to replace her in the series'
third year, producers have said they will more likely deal with
Tony's conflicted feelings at losing a parent he disliked.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great fun to be part of a series which has captured so
much attention,'' Marchand, who also had a long, distinguished
theatrical career, once said. ''While I realized I was involved in
a quality production, I had no idea 'The Sopranos' would be a major
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   She called the role a refreshing change of pace from the
''tasteful ladies'' like Mrs. Pynchon that she so often played.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 1622 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
