<DOCNO> APW20000720.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP boss: Hillary Clinton an angry woman driven by blind political ambition </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Accusing Senate candidate Hillary Rodham
Clinton of being ''an angry woman'' driven by ''blind political
ambition,'' the head of New York's Republican Party says voters
should reject her in part because ''she didn't send Chelsea to
school here.''
</P>
<P>
   In a copy of a fund-raising letter obtained Thursday by The
Associated Press, state GOP Chairman William Powers also said the
first lady has ''been at the front and center of every Clinton-Gore
scandal and this has been the most seedy, shameless and corrupt
administration in American history.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Morality matters and character counts and by her own words,
deeds and actions Hillary Rodham Clinton has disqualified herself
from earning the public's trust, let alone public office,'' Powers
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the second harsh letter from Powers to surface in a
week. The first one called the first lady ''cold-blooded and hot
hotheaded'' and denounced her as a ''shrill and scheming person.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers is a major supporter of Clinton's Republican rival for
the Senate, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said, ''These negative
letters signal that Rick Lazio and the GOP have no intention of
running a campaign on the issues. We are confident that New Yorkers
will reject Rick Lazio's campaign of insults and personal
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, Powers defended his mailings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm told we have three more in the bank ready to go and we're
just going to keep mailing them,'' the party chairman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's helping raise money - a lot of money ... I've never seen
a response to direct mail like we're getting from her,'' Powers
added.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the harsh words in his letters, Powers said that unlike
his feelings for Vice President Al Gore, ''I respect her.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I just don't like him. I think he's a phony,'' Powers said of
the vice president. ''I don't respect this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to rate the first lady on a scale of one to 10, if Gore
was at the worst end of the scale as a 10, Powers said, ''Hillary's
not a 10; maybe a five.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, on the front of Powers' desk lay a bumper sticker
that said, ''Kiss my N.Y. ass Hillary.'' Powers said someone had
mailed it to him.
</P>
<P>
   The party leader defended his use of Chelsea Clinton's name in
the mailing as a way of attacking the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just pointing out that she's not a New Yorker ... It's
just a comparison with Lazio. His children have gone to school in
New York,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   Powers' own three grown sons all went to New York schools from
the time they were children through college and graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   In appealing for money with charges that Clinton is a
carpetbagger and scandal-scarred, Powers also claims in the second
letter that Republicans are up against ''the biased New York press,
the New York City Labor Bosses, Manhattan's limousine liberals and
the out-of-town crowd from Washington, D.C. and Hollywood,
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers' letter said he needs the help to ''stop this ambitious,
ruthless, scheming, calculating, manipulating woman from fooling
voters into thinking 'she's one of us.''' He asks potential donors
''to stand up to the outsiders who mock our New York values and
scoff at our commonsense conservatism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
