<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Long Form May Be Replaced  </HEADLINE>
By GENARO C. ARMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Census Bureau's director sought Thursday
to persuade lawmakers to adopt his plan to replace the 53-question
long form for the 2010 census with a similar questionnaire
administered every year.
</P>
<P>
   The American Community Survey would ask questions similar to
those now on the long form, Kenneth Prewitt told the House
Government Reform's census subcommittee. He hopes to begin the
survey in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the survey would provide more timely statistics
essential to federal, state and local governments. Until now, they
must rely either on census data as old as 10 years or on
statistical projections.
</P>
<P>
   ''The American Community Survey is the single most important
innovation in federal household statistics in more than a
half-century, and positions the country well for the century we are
just entering,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey would eliminate the need to collect long form data
every 10 years during the actual census, supporters say. It would
ask many of the same questions from this year's long form, such as
a respondent's income and race.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee chairman, Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., questioned
whether the survey would address concerns raised by top Republicans
in the spring that the long form was too intrusive. Though the
Census Bureau can implement the new survey without lawmakers'
approval, it must essentially secure funds and support from
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be a disservice to the American people if we were to
reflexively approve the American Community Survey in the wake of
the long form controversy, without giving it careful consideration
to determine if it addresses today's privacy concerns,'' Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt believes these concerns could be better answered because
a smaller, randomly selected number of households would be surveyed
-- 3 million each year, or 250,000 a month, rather than the roughly
20 million households mailed a long form this year. That would
enable professional census-takers to handle the survey, rather than
some of the 440,000 temporary, part-time enumerators who visited
homes the past three months, Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said a test of the new survey in 31 communities produced
a 97 percent response rate. The mail response rate for Census 2000
was 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It would cost about $6.1 billion to conduct the survey and the
2010 Census -- the same amount it cost to conduct Census 2000,
Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses were optimistic about the proposed survey but
await a final plan.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Welty, president of the board of directors of the
National Center for Small Communities, said the survey could give
rural governments access to more recent demographic information
that big cities can get on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also heard testimony from Rep. Mac Collins, R-Ga.,
over his legislation to eliminate a $100 fine that can be assessed
to people who do not answer questions unrelated to apportionment on
Census 2000 forms. The fine has not been assessed in decades,
Collins said, so there is no need for it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The complexity of the census long form and the threat of
financial penalties is actually counterproductive,'' Collins said.
''They intimidate Americans and lead to lower participation in the
census.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn Maloney of New York, the subcommittee's ranking
Democrat, pointed out that the 66 percent response rate this year
was five percentage points higher than the last count in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Census Bureau: http://www.census.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Center for Small Communities: http://natat.org/ncsc/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
