<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Summit Drags On  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, with
furrowed brow, takes notes on a white legal pad as President
Clinton looks on, his eyes puffy with fatigue. Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat hunches over a picnic table listening stone-faced as
the president talks.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen- to 20-hour days are the norm at the summit, which
began July 11 -- 65 days before a Sept. 13 target deadline for a
permanent status agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no naps,'' a State Department official said
Thursday, adding that negotiators at the Camp David presidential
retreat are drinking lots of caffeinated cola. ''Arafat and Barak
are night people.''
</P>
<P>
   It opened on a jocular note: You first! No, after you! Following
Clinton into Aspen cabin for their first three-way chat, Arafat and
Barak wrestled playfully, each trying to usher the other through
the door. Barak eventually succeeded in pushing Arafat through the
doorway first.
</P>
<P>
   The clowning didn't last long. The summit soon turned serious.
Many nights, discussions continued well past midnight. The
president's work day Monday lasted until 5 a.m. the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   A photo shows Arafat and Secretary Madeleine Albright walking
one night, hand-in-hand, an aide illuminating the path with a
flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's face did not hide his exhaustion. But Barak, a highly
disciplined career military man, rarely shows any public signs of
fatigue, even after grueling late-night work sessions. And
70-year-old Arafat, despite health problems, displays a sometimes
astonishing stamina, swiftly recovering from overnight meetings -- a
lifelong habit -- with only a few hours of sleep. Arafat's aides
joke that he will outlive them all.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton held talks, on issues that have divided the two sides
for 52 years, on a stone patio edged with tiki torches and in
wood-paneled rooms, decorated with comfy floral chintz sofas and
chairs. There were discussions over breakfasts and dinners, in golf
carts and during walks through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was informal -- and so was the attire. In a
Jerusalem newspaper, top Israeli fashion designers gave Clinton a
thumbs-up for his jeans, polo shirts, a white Arkansas Razorbacks
sweat shirt. Barak went casual too with a denim shirt and a tan
baseball cap that the designers called a fashion don't. They were
disappointed that Arafat stayed with his army-style fatigues, but
he got kudos for keeping on his trademark checkered kaffiyeh.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were blanketed by a news blackout, but Lockhart did
share a few details: Clinton strolled with his dog, Buddy, and
watched the All-Star baseball game with daughter, Chelsea. The
delegations dined on beef tenderloin and sun-dried tomatoes and
salmon with Thai curry sauce. There was a ''fender-bender'' between
two golf carts driven by two negotiators ''on the same side.'' A
senior American diplomat ''wiped out'' on a bike.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reported Sunday that he was more ''optimistic'' than
when he first arrived. ''But I would be totally misleading if I
said I had an inkling that a deal is at hand,'' he told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The talks heated up Monday as the clock ticked toward Clinton's
scheduled departure on Wednesday for an eight-nation economic
summit in Japan. Lockhart insisted Clinton was leaving as
scheduled. At midnight Tuesday, the White House announced he would
delay his departure for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors flew all day Wednesday. One report had Arafat threatening
to pack his bags, another that Barak was walking out.
</P>
<P>
   No one outside the compound knew, or would say, what was going
on, but White House photos -- taken early Wednesday before the talks
collapsed and restarted -- foreshadowed the tense diplomatic drama
that would play out past midnight under a steady drizzle. One shows
Clinton looking pensive and tired, his head resting on his left
hand as he listens to Arafat. Another shows Clinton, posed the
same, listening to a serious-faced Barak leaning forward to talk to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Talks were nearing collapse. Lockhart would later admit that
Clinton's temper had flared ''a few times.'' The president shuttled
between the Israeli and Palestinian cabins in a desperate mission
to salvage the summit. But shortly before 11 p.m., in a 28-word
statement, the White House tersely pronounced the summit over --
without an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A motorcade of vans and limousines, their headlights blurred by
thick fog, assembled in front of the president's cabin. It was time
to go to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a dramatic turn in the high-stakes summit: Arafat and
Barak would stay on while Clinton went abroad. Albright would
broker the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sorry to keep you up,'' a weary Clinton told reporters who had
been waiting for hours for the finale of a summit that enters Day
11 on Friday. Clinton's words, which usually flow from his lips
with the ease of a polished politician, were metered. He was
slightly hoarse.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all thought it was over ... and then we discovered that
nobody wanted to quit. Nobody wanted to give up,'' Clinton said.
Then he added: ''You should draw no inference from this. This is
really, really hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
