<HEADLINE> Archbishop undergoes knee surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Archbishop Edward Egan had surgery on his left
knee on Thursday, a successful procedure to mend torn cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   The 1&AMP;frac12;-hour operation on the Roman Catholic prelate was
performed at St. Vincent's Medical Center in Bridgeport, Conn.,
said Joseph Zwilling, his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, the former bishop of Bridgeport, succeeded the late
Cardinal John O'Connor as spiritual leader of New York's 2.4
million Roman Catholics last month.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-year-old archbishop has had knee trouble since last fall,
said Zwilling, and the surgery on his left knee was recommended by
his orthopedist in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling described it as an arthroscopic procedure ''to address
a meniscal tear.'' It was performed under spinal anesthesia with
sedation, said St. Vincent's spokesman Bruce Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   The meniscus is a piece of cartilage in the middle of the knee
that acts as a shock absorber during weight-bearing activities. A
meniscal tear can occur when the knee is forcefully twisted.
</P>
<P>
   Egan twisted his knee last November, after which he has
experienced swelling and discomfort, Hutchison said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
