<DOCNO> APW20000720.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson to OPEC: Boost Output  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson urged OPEC
Thursday to boost production and help bring down U.S. gas prices
that he said remain ''unacceptably high.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, regular gasoline is selling for an average of $1.55
a gallon, down from $1.68 a gallon a month ago, Richardson said. In
the Midwest, where many motorists had been paying well over $2 a
gallon for gas, the cost of cleaner-burning gasoline has fallen 48
cents in a month and conventional gas is 20 cents less; both types
of gas now are cheaper than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ''Still, they're unacceptably high,'' Richardson told the Senate
Agriculture Committee, which is examining the effects of soaring
energy costs on farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson commended the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries for two oil output increases in May and June. He also
praised Saudi Arabia, which has called for a production boost with
or without the rest of its OPEC partners.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, recent statements by OPEC leaders have created
confusion about what the cartel will do.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope they continue to keep an open mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC President Ali Rodriguez last week said that the time was
not right for new output increases. But this week, he reaffirmed
his commitment to a system that triggers production increases when
OPEC crude remains high for too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
