<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'The in Crowd'  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTY LEMIRE
For The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ''Wild Things'' came out in 1998, you could tell it was
trying to be campy beneath its sleazy surface. That's what made the
movie fun -- it was so bad, it was almost good.
</P>
<P>
   ''The in Crowd'' has many of the same elements -- the sultry
Southern setting, the clash of rich and poor, the knockdown,
drag-out, lipstick brawls. But it tries to be a serious thriller,
so it's just plain bad.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell it's bad without spending a dime at the multiplex.
You see, the studio wouldn't screen it for us mean old film critics
ahead of time. But here's what this reviewer and six other people
saw at a recent matinee:
</P>
<P>
   Adrien (Lori Heuring) has just been released from a psychiatric
hospital, where she was treated for erotomania, which probably was
the affliction of choice because it sounds naughty. She had sexual
fantasies about her school psychologist and then smashed the
windshield on his car with a hockey stick when he rejected her.
</P>
<P>
   A sympathetic doctor at the hospital (Daniel Hugh Kelly)
arranges a job for her at the South Carolina country club where he
belongs. Perfect -- she'll fit right in.
</P>
<P>
   Adrien folds beach towels, serves champagne and finds out fast
about the obnoxious, stuck-up college kids who are home for the
summer, the titular ''in crowd.'' It's ''Girl, Interrupted'' meets
''The Flamingo Kid.''
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of exposition early on, so we don't get these
complex characters mixed up. Another employee explains that Sheila
(Erinn Bartlett) is the ''blonde bombshell,'' and that Brittany
(Susan Ward) is ''the queen.'' But that's obvious, because Brittany
looks like Yasmine Bleeth from ''Baywatch,'' when she walks, it's
in slow motion, and all the rich old guys at the country club ogle
her.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, Brittany is drawn to Adrien, and invites her to
join her elite group of nondescript friends. Brittany buys Adrien
gifts, holds her hand when they walk, takes her out at night and
gratuitously writhes against her on the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   But Matt the tennis pro (Matthew Settle), the object of
Brittany's affections, starts flirting with Adrien. Brittany
doesn't like this and turns evil. Screenwriters Mark Gibson and
Philip Halprin make her say menacing things like, ''I brought you
in ... I can just as easily throw you out.''
</P>
<P>
   Right around this time, dark secrets from the past rear their
ugly heads. People overhear conversations at the most opportune
moments. It's standard -- but not terribly interesting -- thriller
fare.
</P>
<P>
   Besides bad writing and bad acting, the lighting is poor and the
colors are faded.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are little continuity lapses. For example, Adrien
walks into a room and her long, blonde hair is down. A few seconds
later, she walks out and her hair is pulled up in a clip. But
really, who's paying attention?
</P>
<P>
   Watching these shallow, flashy people isn't even a guilty
pleasure. The movie feels like the pilot for a nighttime soap opera
-- one that's doomed for cancellation midseason.
</P>
<P>
   ''The in Crowd,'' a Warner Bros. release, was directed by Mary
Lambert (''Pet Sematary''). It's rated PG-13 for violence,
sexuality, language and some drug content. Running time: 108
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
