<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Staten Islanders being cautious after first West Nile spraying  </HEADLINE>
By JUDIE GLAVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The ball pit was empty and the wavy, red slide
abandoned by the toddlers whose giggles can usually be heard in the
play yard at the Friends day care center on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at the wooded, Clay Pit Ponds state preserve were armed
with cans of bug repellent and Adriana Robotti's three daughters
rode bicycles instead of swimming in their pool after the city
began the first round of insecticide spraying this summer to
eradicate potential West Nile virus-carrying mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Two dead crows carrying the virus were found in the Rossville
and Westerleigh sections of Staten Island, the only borough where
the disease has showed up to date.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last summer's spraying efforts, more than two dozen
dead, infected crows have also shown up in parts of Westchester and
Rockland counties. Virus-carrying mosquitoes were also found in
Suffolk County. All three suburban areas are scheduled to begin
spraying as soon as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns were heightened after a 71-year-old man visiting from
South Carolina died Wednesday at St. Vincent's Hospital on Staten
Island after being hospitalized with West Nile-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Thursday that initial tests done
by the city Health Department showed the man, whose name has not
been released, did not have the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   ''The determination was made that it was not West Nile,'' said
Giuliani. Health Commissioner Neal Cohen said the cause of death is
still unclear. ''We don't know,'' he said. ''It's premature at this
point. We may never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said Wednesday the man had many other health problems
and noted that other viruses including encephalitis and meningitis
have the same symptoms as West Nile: muscle aches, stiff neck and
flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   But the news did little to ease the minds of Staten Islanders,
who battled with the twin concerns of virus-carrying mosquitoes and
the effects of chemical spraying.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel a little like a mosquito myself - trapped,'' Robotti
said. ''I can't lock the kids in the house the rest of the summer.
It's crazy and more than a little scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband asked the kids - ages 8 to 13 - to stay out of the
pool Thursday, after city officials sprayed the insecticide Anvil
throughout Robotti's Rossville neighborhood during the early
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a coalition of environmental groups and activists
sued the city to stop the spraying, claiming the effects of the
insecticide - a synthetic chemical similar to the natural
ingredient produced by chrysanthemums - was harmful to humans, fish
and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ''We find that these insecticides they are spraying are far
worse than any kind of ailment in the city,'' Mitchell Cohen, a
member of the No Spray Coalition Against the Misuse of Pesticides,
said outside U.S. District Court in Manhattan where the lawsuit was
filed.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which includes members of Disabled in Action, Save
Organic Standards and the National Coalition Against the Misuse of
Pesticides, says the city is violating federal and state laws and
is seeking civil penalties of $27,500 each time the city sprays
without the proper state or federal permit.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition says the insecticides can cause dizziness,
headaches, nausea, vomiting, skin irritation, loss of coordination,
twitching and seizures in some people. They also said they may be a
cause of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Daidone, the co-owner of the Friends preschool and day care
center in Rossville, was taking all precautions against both bugs
and the spray that might kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Her dozen two-to-five year old charges stayed inside doing art
projects Thursday instead of playing in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hate keeping them inside on such a beautiful summer day,''
she said, ''but I'm not taking any chances,'' especially since one
of the dead crows was found just two blocks from the school.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 New Yorkers have been tested this year for the
West Nile virus, but none have proved positive, state Health
Department spokesman John Signor said.
</P>
<P>
   However, CDC spokeswoman Barbara Reynolds said Wednesday that
they expect it will show up at some point.
</P>
<P>
   Seven deaths and 60 cases were attributed to the virus last
year. Left untreated, West Nile can result in encephalitis, or a
swelling of the brain. The elderly and those with compromised
immune systems are most at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
