<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Injured ticket agent: Airport failed to guard against 'air rage'  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The Continental Airlines ticket agent
injured a year ago in a confrontation with a delayed passenger
claims the operator of Newark International Airport should have
anticipated unruly behavior from angry travelers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey
failed to make the airport safe even though it knew of prior
''anti-social behavior'' by passengers, agent Angelo Sottile
charges in a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Sottile also sued the passenger, John C. Davis Jr., of
Fredricksburg, Va., claiming Davis put him in a bear hug and
slammed him headfirst onto the floor; and Haynes Security Inc., of
Newark, charging the company failed in its duties at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Sottile, 51, of Kearny, seeks unspecified monetary compensation
for ''severe and debilitating injuries to his head and neck'' and
''serious psychological injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 30, faces trial in the fall for aggravated assault. The
charge carries up to 10 years in prison. Sottile was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   The incident prompted Continental to launch a national campaign
last summer against ''air rage.''
</P>
<P>
   Port Authority spokesman Peter Yerkes said Thursday the agency
does not generally comment on pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Davis lawyer Anthony J. Pope Jr. said Thursday his client was
acting in self-defense and as a Virginia resident is not under the
jurisdiction of the lawsuit, which was filed Wednesday in state
Superior Court for Hudson County, in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left Thursday seeking comment from Haynes were not
immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Continental spokeswoman Catherine Stengel said Sottile has not
yet returned to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's just concentrating on getting better, and we hope that he
does,'' Stengel said.
</P>
<P>
   Sottile did not immediately respond to a message left at his
home Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Louis J. Lamatina, said Sottile lost 60 percent of
the motion in his neck, which suffered two broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   ''He can't turn his head too fast or too far,'' Lamatina said.
</P>
<P>
   ''My guy has no memory of what happened. He was in a coma for
five days,'' the lawyer said. ''But he doesn't hold a grudge.''
</P>
<P>
   Sottile has returned to his manager's job at the Kearny Post
Office, but is only working four hours a day, Lamatina said.
</P>
<P>
   He is unlikely to return to his part-time job with Continental:
''I don't think he can do that work anymore; it's standing on his
feet too much,'' Lamatina said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer declined to comment on what the Port Authority or
Haynes should have done to prevent violence.
</P>
<P>
   Continental is not being sued because New Jersey only allows
employees to seek relief through workers' compensation, Lamatina
said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident took place July 22, 1999, at Gate 115 on the lower
level of Terminal C, a windowless area the lawsuit said is called
''the dungeon'' by Continental workers.
</P>
<P>
   Many flights around the country, including the Davis family
flight to Orlando, Fla., were delayed because of weather, the
lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and 10 others, including his in-laws and five children,
were en route to a Disney World vacation, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the bathrooms in that area were closed for renovations
that day, and tempers flared as the waiting area became crowded and
warm, with passengers yelling at ticket agents, including Sottile,
the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis flight began boarding about 9 p.m., about 2&AMP;frac14; hours
after its scheduled departure when one of his children ran into the
jetway, the enclosed walkway connecting the terminal with the
plane, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts differ as to what happened next.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague of Sottile stopped Davis' wife from following her
daughter, saying she could not enter the jetway without a boarding
pass, and that worker went to get the child, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Sottile then took his colleague's place and told Davis he could
not enter the jetway yet.
</P>
<P>
   Davis then grabbed Sottile and slammed him headfirst onto the
floor, police and the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and his family said Sottile was belligerent, pushed Davis'
wife as she tried to enter the jetway and then put his hands around
Davis' neck when he came to his wife's aid.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had filed a lawsuit against Continental Airlines, charging
that the Houston-based carrier's poor training caused employees to
be hostile to travelers, but it was dismissed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
