<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Launch Ad Campaign  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a televised attack against Rep. Jim Rogan
in California, House Democrats have quietly launched an advertising
effort eventually expected to cost millions and spread to dozens of
races, a key part of an effort to win a majority this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Smith, a spokesman for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, declined comment on the commercial, which began
airing July 6 on cable stations and accuses Rogan of voting against
funding to reduce classroom size. ''We're not going to telegraph
our strategies for Republicans'' to know in advance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan, who played a prominent role in President Clinton's
impeachment proceedings, accused Democrats of broadcasting a
''lying distortion'' of his record. Locked in a fiercely
competitive race, he said he hoped the GOP campaign committee would
respond on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the particulars of Rogan's effort to fend off a challenge
from State Sen. Adam Schiff, several Democratic officials described
the 30-second advertisement as the first in what is planned as wave
after wave of commercials in targeted districts.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising is expected to begin airing soon in another
California district, possibly as early as next week, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   These Democrats spoke only on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they have the money to mount efforts in as many
as 50 districts, involving get-out-the-vote activities, radio and
television advertising and other campaign activities. This year,
unlike in past campaigns, Democrat say they will air commercials
tailored to individual situations.
</P>
<P>
   One official said other commercials will touch on debt
repayment, prescription drugs for Medicare, gun control, a
patients' bill of rights and other key Democratic campaign themes.
</P>
<P>
   A switch of six or seven seats in this fall's elections would
give Democrats a majority in the Congress that convenes in January
2001. Republicans, too, will spend millions on commercials as part
of their effort to hold control.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Democrats are wasting their money right now,'' argued Jim
Wilkinson, a spokesman for the GOP campaign committee. ''Our ad
programs will come later in the year when voters are actually
paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats, with a hefty cash advantage -- $37 million in
the bank compared with $22 million for the GOP -- were able to
strike first.
</P>
<P>
   In Rogan, they picked a GOP incumbent who has won two terms
without gaining as much as 51 percent of the vote and who has a
well-funded opponent familiar to local voters. Rogan's high-profile
role in impeachment added to his attractiveness as a target.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial, expected to stay on the air for several more
weeks, accuses Rogan of voting against funding ''that would reduce
overcrowding in California's classroom. Call Jim Rogan. Tell him to
start voting for new, qualified teachers and smaller class size,''
it says.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Rogan said he had voted to fund 120,000 new
teacher positions, but against a Democratic proposal to dictate how
federal funds were to be spent. ''It's a typical DCCC
cookie-cutter, lying distortion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial was developed and aired under the Byzantine rules
that govern political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   It is an example of ''issue advocacy,'' meaning it contains no
explicit call for Rogan's defeat or for Schiff's election. In fact,
Schiff's name is not mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is no direct advocacy, the commercial is paid for
with a blend of hard money -- relatively difficult to raise because
individual donations are limited in size -- and soft money, which
can be raised in larger amounts.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial bears a tagline that says it was paid for by the
California Democratic Party. But the state chairman, Art Torres, as
well as officials in Washington, say the money was being
transferred by the national party committee. Torres put the cost of
the advertising at $126,000 in two separate purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is based on research conducted by DCCC staff and was
produced by the firm of Morris, Carrick and Guma, one of two
companies tapped to handle millions of dollars in DCCC commercials
this campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   Because federal law appears to limit direct coordination between
the DCCC and Schiff's campaign, officials say they did not notify
their candidate in advance. Still, it dovetails nicely with a
commercial the Schiff campaign is running that says he ''fought to
reduce class sizes''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it is a textbook example of how outside advertisements can
effectively stretch a candidate's budget -- or, in Rogan's case,
force a candidate to re-evaluate his own strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Roe, a spokesman for Rogan, said his campaign is currently
off the air after running several weeks worth of commercials. Rogan
declined to say whether he would respond with new ads of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he hopes the GOP campaign committee will respond,
he said, ''Yes ... I assume they'll respond to protect me and
expose Schiff's record.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Davis, who chairs the GOP campaign effort, pledged to
do as much. ''We're going to make sure that they're responded to
appropriately and the record is set straight,'' said the Virginia
lawmaker....
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic Campaign Committee:
http://www.takebackthehouse.com
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Campaign Committee: http://www.nrcc.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 1748 </TRAILER>
