<HEADLINE> Mitchell: NIreland Peace Inevitable  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Progress toward peace in Northern Ireland is
irreversible, the broker of the province's 1998 peace accord said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell chaired the negotiations that
led to the Good Friday accord, which laid the groundwork for a new
power-sharing government in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   When he agreed to oversee peace talks between the province's
fractious Protestant and Catholic political parties in 1995, he
thought there was ''little or no prospect'' of a solution, he told
the American Bar Association's annual meeting in London.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Mitchell said he believes long-term peace is
inevitable -- despite setbacks such as the discovery of a bomb on a
London railway line Wednesday. The device, believed to have been
planted by a Catholic paramilitary group opposed to the peace
process, was detonated harmlessly by police but caused commuter
chaos across the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''As with all such conflicts, as hard as it is to get agreement,
implementation is even more difficult,'' Mitchell said. ''We are
seeing the difficulties of implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said the province's economy would expand once its
fledgling institutions become firmly established.
</P>
<P>
   ''While it will take a long time to achieve genuine
reconciliation, I believe a durable peace is clearly on its way,
and I think there will be a remarkable explosion of economic
growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an advanced society. These are very intelligent,
impressive, productive people and I think, once they get that
political stability, they will experience growth with which they
are not familiar in their history,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 1750 </TRAILER>
