<DOCNO> APW20000720.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Joblessness Rises  </HEADLINE>
By TO MUSE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- After weeks of protests over
Argentina's high jobless rate, the government delivered more bad
news Thursday: the official unemployment rate remains stubbornly
high, topping 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pledges an economic recovery is imminent, President
Fernando De la Rua's government announced national joblessness has
edged up to 15.4 percent. That compares with 13.8 percent in
October, the last time figures were released.
</P>
<P>
   The news only darkened hopes for economic revival in Argentina,
which is struggling more than regional giant Brazil to pull itself
out of a region-wide recession. Continued high unemployment is only
causing more pessimism in a country struggling since Brazil
devalued its currency last January, prompting a regional slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment report, released three times yearly, is the
latest evidence that De la Rua's bold austerity plan of deep
spending cuts and higher taxes may not be enough to immediately
reactivate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Sappia, a Labor Ministry official, said the increase was
worrisome. ''Seeing these numbers ... it shows the country is not
well,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Double-digit unemployment has haunted Argentina since 1994 --
even during periods of high growth. The government has forecast 3.5
percent growth this year. But independent economists estimate
growth of no more than 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though the latest figure is smaller than the nadir of 18.4
percent reached in May 1995, it still has analysts worried that a
turnaround will be slow to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Joblessness has been especially acute in Argentina's
impoverished provinces.
</P>
<P>
   In Resistencia, a northeastern Argentine city, jobless
demonstrators demanding work threw rocks and battled with police,
who responded with tear gas and batons. No serious injuries were
reported in what was the latest in a series of scattered protests
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, some 1,000 jobseekers turned out several weeks ago
when a huge supermarket in Mendoza, western Argentina, offered 100
jobs. Hundreds lined up this week for 30 vacancies at a Buenos
Aires factory that makes alfajores -- a traditional Argentine
pastry.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Gonzalez, 43, lost work as a carpenter eight years ago.
With too few jobs available, he now sells bags of peanuts on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economic system is sweeping us into the streets,'' said
Gonzalez. ''There is too little work, too much unemployment.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists said Argentina's high unemployment could partly be
blamed on a drop-off in construction jobs and on labor laws that
remain overly rigid -- despite recent and hard-won reforms by De la
Rua's government.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Gloria Sorensen of Banco Frances also cited a rise in
the supply of labor as women and young people join the labor market
at a faster pace than jobs can be created.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
