<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State unveils new multimedia anti-smoking program  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - After doing 30 seconds' worth of jumping
jacks, 11-year-old Alfredo Echevarria blew through straws of
varying widths.
</P>
<P>
   They started out wide, and ended up as narrow as a coffee
stirrer.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford sixth-grader demonstrated how hard it was to
breathe as his lungs got more constricted - just what would happen
if he smoked a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of a handful of activities on display Thursday at the
M.D. Fox School as state education officials unveiled a new
multimedia anti-smoking program. Called Science, Tobacco &AMP; You, the
program incorporates digital photography, computer modeling and
hands-on activities to show students the effects of tobacco on
their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million program is funded from the $3.6 billion tobacco
settlement Connecticut won in a 1998 class action lawsuit against
the industry, said Maraide Sullivan, a manager with the state's
Office of Policy and Management. The optional program will be
offered to schools at no cost and is expected to be in 1,100
fourth- and fifth-grade classrooms this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Already 200 teachers from across the state have signed up for
training sessions next month, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   The program was launched in Florida in 1998, and is now used in
4,000 classrooms there, said Sam Spiegel, a Florida State
University professor who helped develop the program.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to tell if the program will stop kids from
smoking as middle schoolers, Spiegel said. But initial studies show
that students have shifted their attitudes and behaviors toward
tobacco, become more knowledgeable about smoking and improved their
standardized test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nowhere in the program do we say 'Don't smoke,''' he said.
''We're giving them more than a message. We're giving them
knowledge and tools to make a good decision.
</P>
<P>
   And teacher reaction, Spiegel added, ''is off the charts.''
Teachers like the fact that the program is not an additional part
of the school day; rather, he said, it's way for them combine
science, health, math, social studies and language arts in one
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Although Florida and Connecticut are so far the only states that
offer the program on a statewide level, Spiegel said other states -
including Massachusetts, California and Texas - are looking into
it.
</P>
<P>
   The students seemed to agree that the program would effectively
pass on the message that smoking is dangerous, not cool.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a very good way to show you how to take care of
yourself,'' said Allie Cipolla, 9, a Canton fourth grader. ''If it
teaches you a lesson, it probably means you won't end up smoking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
