<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> September bear hunt now appears likely  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - With no new legislative action scheduled,
the state's first bear hunt in almost 30 years appears on track to
begin Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The state New Jersey Fish and Game Council voted unanimously
last month to approve the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, the state Senate with a 31-7 vote approved a bill
that would halt the hunt. An Assembly version of that measure has
yet to be scheduled for a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Assembly Agricultural and Natural Resources
Committee now says the bill will not be heard before the hunt
begins.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we should be overruling Fish and Game when
they're acting prudently,'' Assemblyman John C. Gibson, R-Cape May,
told The Record of Hackensack for its Thursday editions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've gotten dozens of bills referred to me. I pick those that
are in the best interest of the state and have the best chance of
being processed,'' he told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The full Assembly is in recess. A similar proposal to ban a bear
hunt cleared a committee in 1997, but was never scheduled for a
vote on the Assembly floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish and Game Council cleared the way for the first hunt
since 1971 in an effort to reduce the state's burgeoning bear
population. Reported incidents of contact between bears and humans
have increased dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of many northern New Jersey communities complain that
the bears invade back yards, kill pets and scare children.
Complaints of damage by black bears have soared from 285 in 1995 to
1,659 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have tried ''aversion conditioning'' to scare
off bears with pepper spray or rubber buckshot and urged residents
not to feed bears and to bring their garbage indoors at night.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, there were fewer than 100 black bears in New
Jersey. It is estimated that more than 1,100 bears now live in 11
of the state's 21 counties.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the bear population in residential areas has
grown in part because of residential development in former rural
areas. Hunting seasons in neighboring New York and Pennsylvania may
have also pushed bears to New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
