<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki aide grilled in bribery trial  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A top campaign aide to Gov. George Pataki
endured a daylong grilling Thursday by federal prosecutors, who
labeled him a suspect in a scheme to secure the early release of
violent felons in exchange for contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ''You understand, as you sit here today, you are a target of an
investigation of the United States Attorney's office into federal
bribery - you understand that, right?'' prosecutor Margaret
Giordano asked the aide, Patrick Donohue, at a trial in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, ma'am,'' replied Donohue, finance director for ''Friends
of Pataki.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Giordano pressured Donohue to concede that ''if
you admitted that you were involved in this scheme, you would lose
your job tomorrow.'' The judge struck the question before he could
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue - called as a defense witness in a campaign corruption
case against Korean-American businessman Yung Soo Yoo - has not
been charged with any crime, and the governor's office denies any
wrongdoing. Outside court, Donohue's lawyer called the ongoing
pay-for-parole probe a ''witchhunt.''
</P>
<P>
   But the investigation has dogged the administration at a time
when Pataki is being considered as a running mate for presidential
nominee George W. Bush. Donohue, 29, meanwhile, has continued
raising money for Pataki, the Republican party and U.S. Senate
hopeful Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Called to the stand Thursday, Donohue repeatly denied teaming
with Yoo to broker deals guaranteeing three sets of Korean-American
parents that campaign contributions totaling more than $36,000
would result in parole for their inmate sons.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue admitted meeting with a Queens pastor whose son,
convicted robber and gang member John Kim, was paroled in 1996
after the family arranged for more than $7,000 in donations to the
Pataki campaign. A former parole official testified Wednesday that
the commissioners who voted for Kim's release had been told that
the governor wanted him set free.
</P>
<P>
   But Donohue claimed that when he accepted money, he was unaware
the donors had children in prison. He also said he returned it when
he learned they thought there was quid pro quo.
</P>
<P>
   ''Was (Kim's father) promised anything in exchange for his
contribution?'' asked Yoo's attorney, Nicholas DeFeis.
</P>
<P>
   ''No, sir,'' Donohue responded.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, prosecutors charged that internal memos,
testimony by the parents and secretly recorded conversations show
Donohue illicitly lobbied behind the scenes for the prisoners'
release. They confronted him with tapes in which he could be heard
telling the brother of one convict that he had forwarded paperwork
to the governor's counsel's office - which handles clemency
applications - and that a solution was ''in the works.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue admitted contacting administration insiders about the
inmates, but only to help the families learn more about their legal
status.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is it your testimony today that you were not trying to help
(the inmates) get released somehow?'' Giordano asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just trying to get a status,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Donohue refused to speak to reporters. But his
attorney, Tom Puccio, accused prosecutors of trying to use his
innocent client ''to tar Mr. Yoo.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This has been a witchhunt from day one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yoo case stems from a grand jury investigation of an alleged
influence peddling by Pataki aides in parole cases. So far three
parole officials have been either charged or convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo, 63, of Glen Ridge, N.J., faces up to 10 years in prison if
convicted on corruption and obstruction of justice charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-20-00 1810 </TRAILER>
