<DOCNO> APW20000720.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Denies Pinochet Allegations  </HEADLINE>
By EDUARDO GALLARDO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- A lawyer for Gen. Augusto Pinochet told
Chile's Supreme Court Thursday that the ex-dictator did not order
the executions and kidnappings allegedly carried out in the opening
days of his regime in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Rivadeneira also told the court that the military junta
then ruling Chile, not Pinochet, was behind the military squad
responsible for the ''caravan of death,'' in which 72 jailed
dissidents were dragged from their cells and executed shortly after
Pinochet seized power in a coup. Nineteen of the victims have never
been found.
</P>
<P>
   Rivadeneira argued for 90 minutes before the court, which is
hearing Pinochet's appeal of a lower tribunal ruling last month
that stripped him of his congressional immunity.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling allowed his trial to go forward, but the current
appeal could prevent that.
</P>
<P>
   Three attorneys representing relatives of the victims insisted
that as leader of the four-man junta that ran Chile, Pinochet held
absolute power after the coup in which Marxist President Salvador
Allende was toppled.
</P>
<P>
   Rivadeneira also revived his claim that the ailing Pinochet
cannot obtain a fair trial, saying his poor health prevents him
from organizing a proper defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''I myself have not been able to have direct contact with Gen.
Pinochet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Eduardo Contreras, representing communist leader Gladys
Marin, one of the plaintiffs, ironically recalled before the court
that Pinochet in recent weeks has received a number of visits.
Those included former aides, retired military men, ''even a
mariachi band.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that the commander of the caravan, Gen. Sergio
Arellano, was acting as ''a delegate of Pinochet'' in the cities
where the executions took place.
</P>
<P>
   As the day before when the hearings opened to decide whether the
former dictator should be tried, small groups of Pinochet foes and
backers peacefully demonstrated under the rain outside the court
building.
</P>
<P>
   Police kept them one block apart ''which meant that only very
minor incidents occurred,'' said police Maj. Jaime Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Rivadeneira also argued that the Supreme Court lacks
jurisdiction over Pinochet because he, as a former chief of state,
should first have been impeached by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gustavo Horvitz, a lawyer for the widow of a journalist killed
by the caravan, said that congress did not even exist under
Pinochet because the former dictator himself closed it after the
coup. Congress reopened in 1990 after Pinochet stepped down from
power.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Insunza, representing the family of a union leader
executed by the caravan, told the court that Pinochet was
responsible ''for the crimes of homicide, kidnapping and illegal
... (burying) of bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Six more anti-Pinochet lawyers will appear in court Friday
before the three days of proceedings end. The court has no deadline
for issuing its ruling, which cannot be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's lawyer say that before the ruling they believe to
determine the former leader's fitness to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, 84, has diabetes, uses a pacemaker and suffered three
mild strokes during 16 months of house detention in London, where
he was released after doctors said he was physically and mentally
unfit to stand trial. He had been detained on a warrant by a
Spanish judge wanting to try him.
</P>
<P>
   The case before the court is one of 146 criminal complaints
filed against the former dictator for deaths and disappearances
blamed on his 1973-90 regime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 1812 </TRAILER>
