<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demonstrations Planned Over Summit  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Supporters and opponents of the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders stepped forward Thursday to make their cases
known before the two sides go back to the negotiating table at Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish settlers commemorated a traditional fast day that recalls
the destruction of ancient Jerusalem by accusing Prime Minister
Ehud Barak of giving up the holy city in modern times. Palestinians
demonstrated urging Yasser Arafat to stand firm.
</P>
<P>
   At President Clinton's urging, the leaders remained at the
retreat near Washington for the weekend, although nine days of
intensive talks aimed at producing a permanent peace accord failed.
Talks are expected to resume when Clinton returns from an economic
summit next week.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli media said the sides were using the break to study
American proposals aimed at unraveling the knottiest disagreements,
over Jerusalem, borders and refugees.
</P>
<P>
   All sides were planning major demonstrations over the weekend.
Peace activists planned a prayer vigil by the Western Wall in
Jerusalem's Old City on Friday. A central square in Tel Aviv is to
be the scene of a mass demonstration against Barak Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this overheated political culture, the rhetoric achieved
an unprecedented apocalyptic tone.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon, a close associate of Barak, warned
of the grim alternatives to a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''An explosion in the talks can lead to other explosions which
might lead to bloodshed,'' Ramon told Israel's army radio.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish settlers also said they were preparing for Palestinian
violence if the summit failed.
</P>
<P>
   Settler leader Pinhas Wallerstein said his settlement recently
purchased nightvision equipment and telescopes for weapons. He is
also requesting additional bullet proof vests for settlement
security guards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone understands Arafat wants a war between us and we need
to prepare ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The army confirmed that it had been providing extra training to
reserves soldiers who live on the settlements. Army chief of staff
Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz has said he fears an intensification of
violence if the talks fail.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians decried such warnings as provocative -- but
echoed them in their own predictions of what failure would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the summit fails, we will enter a black era in the history
of peace process,'' said Communications Minister Imad Fallouji.
''And if we face any Israeli challenges, we are ready and all our
options are open.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Hamas, a militant Islamic group opposed to the
peace process and to Israel's existence, expressed hope the summit
would fail. Hamas planned its own mass rally in Gaza on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's supporters continued their daily demonstrations urging
him to stand firm on all issues, including the release of 1,600
Palestinians jailed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Barak supporters maintaining a peace vigil in Tel Aviv led a
symbolic tour of sights where terror bombers had struck, arguing
that a comprehensive peace deal would end such agonies.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkish opposition leaders said that peace was a worthy goal,
but accused Barak of giving too much away too soon, citing reports
that he was ready for some Palestinian sovereignty in Jerusalem and
had offered about 95 percent of disputed territory.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition Likud party leader Ariel Sharon said those reported
concessions ''set a dangerous precedent that will create an
impossible starting point for future negotiations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 1824 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000720.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miss America Claims Intimidation  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- On the eve of her House testimony in support
of a veterans employment bill, Miss America Heather French says a
high-ranking Clinton administration official was ''trying to
intimidate'' her into changing her position.
</P>
<P>
   While French did not waver in testifying July 12 for a bill the
administration opposed, the Republican chairman of a Veterans'
Affairs subcommittee has demanded an explanation from Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman. Also, the Veterans' Affairs Committee's
top Democrat has told the official to resign.
</P>
<P>
   French said in an interview Thursday that she spoke in a
conference call July 11 with Espiridion Borrego, assistant
secretary of labor for veterans' employment and training, and two
other Labor Department officials. The officials had asked to speak
with her, but she said she did not know the topic would be the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Borrego testified the next day in opposition to key sections of
the bill, which would make major changes in veterans training and
employment programs. The Labor Department, not the Department of
Veterans Affairs, has jurisdiction over these veterans' issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Borrego) never said, 'I would like to change your
opinion,''' but did say the bill ''would cause more than 3,000
veterans to lose their jobs and become homeless,'' French said. ''I
took that as if he was definitely trying to shake my testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation was ''very uncomfortable. I felt they were
trying to intimidate,'' said French, who is engaged to Kentucky Lt.
Gov. Steve Henry, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Borrego did not return a telephone call requesting an interview.
Carl Fillichio, the Labor Department spokesman, said Borrego
''maintains that he never tried to discourage French from
testifying before the subcommittee. Any misinterpretation of his
conversation with French was regrettable.''
</P>
<P>
   Fillichio said the department was in contact with the committee
members and that the department's solicitor and ethics officer
''are conducting a thorough and efficient review of the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after the hearing, Rep. Jack Quinn, R-N.Y., chairman of
the House Veterans' Affairs subcommittee on benefits, wrote Herman
that Borrego tried to convince French to change her mind ''after
she had already submitted her written testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn told Herman that the Labor official ''misrepresented what
the subcommittee's legislation would do, insisted that French
furnish him a copy of her testimony in advance of the hearing and
told French that since she would be appearing with you at a
function ... it would make her support of the ... bill even more
problematical.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Borrego's conduct was ''outrageous'' and that it
''undermines the integrity of the ... hearing process.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lane Evans of Illinois, the committee's ranking Democrat,
wrote Borrego to demand his resignation the day of the hearing.
Evans said the subcommittee staff informed him that Borrego
''suggested'' to French ''that her appearance before the
subcommittee may not be in her best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Such conduct ''could only be taken by someone unfit for a
politically appointed office, regardless of party affiliations,''
Evans wrote.
</P>
<P>
   French, the daughter of a Marine veteran who was wounded in
Vietnam, has made homeless veterans her cause and testified several
times before Congress about their plight.
</P>
<P>
   She said she thought the conversation would be about her
appearance with Herman in Cincinnati last week. Instead, she found
herself on the phone with Borrego and two other Labor Department
officials about the legislation. Fillichio would not identify the
two other officials.
</P>
<P>
   French said she has worked with Borrego previously and he knew
of her strong support for the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was trying to maybe soften me from my view of the bill''
that is supported by major veterans organizations, she said. ''It
was to me unspeakable to think I wouldn't be on the veterans'
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrego did not threaten to cancel the appearance with Herman
and the event took place, French said, adding she did not mention
the phone call to the secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Borrego also criticized provisions that already had been removed
from the legislation, which is still in the Veterans' Affairs
Committee, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The 21st Century Veterans Employment and Training Act would
provide priority to certain veterans in all federally funded
employment and training programs. It also would require government
contractors to take affirmative action to employ qualified
veterans, set an appropriations level for veterans' employment and
training and provide grants to states for their programs.
</P>
<P>
   Borrego said the administration has ''significant concerns''
about the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The priority system should be changed to one that assures
services to veterans under state government programs, Borrego said.
He also had problems with provisions to measure programs'
performance and with a diversion of funds to demonstration projects
in 10 states.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4765.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congressional site: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Labor Department site on veterans' issues:
http://www.dol.gov/dol/vets/
</P>
