<HEADLINE> Clinton says Lazio wrong to oppose FHA expansion  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton blasted GOP Senate
rival Rick Lazio on Thursday for opposing the expansion of a
federal program to help first-time home buyers secure mortgages.
The first lady said it showed the congressman was again kowtowing
to special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know why he would fight so hard against an effort to
make homes affordable to people in his own district and throughout
New York but I can only assume that once again we're seeing a
pattern with him,'' Clinton said in an interview with The
Associated Press late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He supports the mortgage industry's needs over the needs of
his own constituents,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spokesman Bryan Flood called Clinton's comments
''laughable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No one has done more to increase affordable housing in New
York than Rick Lazio,'' Flood said. ''Where has Hillary Clinton
been and what has she done to help homeowners in New York?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Lazio, chairman of the House subcommittee on housing,
opposed a plan to raise caps on the Federal Housing Authority
insurance program, which would make more middle-class people
eligible. Instead, a watered-down version of the plan passed in the
House that expanded the program but by a much smaller percentage
than Democrats and the Department of Housing and Urban Development
had sought.
</P>
<P>
   The House raised the limit on FHA-insured mortgages to a range
of $109,000 to $197,000, depending on the location. HUD, which
oversees the mortgage finance agency, had sought an
across-the-board increase to $227,150.
</P>
<P>
   As first reported by The New York Times, less than one month
after the expansion was scaled back, a political action committee
set up by Lazio in New York received donations totaling $23,500
from six of the largest mortgage insurance companies. The companies
were opposed to the expansion because they believed it would siphon
away their business.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio camp has denied any link between the donations and the
legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to say Thursday whether she believed them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we should leave it to New Yorkers to determine what
kind of connection there was,'' Clinton said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Federal Housing Authority insurance program is
especially important in New York ''because as everybody knows our
cost of housing is very high.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's particularly true in his (Lazio's) own district,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest beneficiaries of the FHA program are
minorities, inner city residents and others who cannot qualify for
conventional mortgages. Most of them are also first-time buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the FHA program, down payments can be as low as 3 percent
and borrowers can use gifts of money from relatives to make the
payments, which conventional lenders generally do not allow.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign filing released this week shows he has
continued to rake in cash from the housing industry since 1998,
although it is dwarfed by the sum he has taken in from the banks
and financial services houses.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio raised some $29,500 in political action committees
representing housing and construction industries since he entered
the race in May, reports show.
</P>
<P>
   He garnered more than $100,000 from the banking and financial
services industry. Those numbers do not contain nations from
individual contributors from the various firms and organizations,
whose donations would drive the total higher.
</P>
<P>
   Among Lazio's largest PAC contributors were Lehman Brothers
($9,000), Arthur Anderson ($8,000), Bank of New York ($8,000) and
Credit Suisse First Boston ($6,000)
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who holds seats on the powerful House banking and
commerce committees, was involved in negotiations over last year's
sweeping financial services modernization bill which allowed banks,
securities firms and insurance companies to merge and sell each
other's products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
