<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federated's Fingerhut unit has costly problems  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CINCINNATI (AP) - Federated Department Stores Inc., the
nationwide retailer whose stable of stores includes Macy's and
Bloomingdale's, is trying to stop multimillion-dollar losses that
bad-debt problems have caused at its Fingerhut direct-to-consumer
sales subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The credit delinquencies will cost $150 million - 43 cents per
share - against second-quarter earnings before interest and taxes,
management said Thursday. Federated said it is moving to fix the
problem, but still expects it could cause pre-tax losses of an
additional $200 million to $250 million this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Tightening access to Fingerhut's credit is one of Federated's
solutions, but that will hurt the catalog sales, management said.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati-based Federated bought Fingerhut Cos. Inc. for $1.7
billion last year to jump-start the retailer's direct-to-customer
sales business. Minneapolis-based Fingerhut brought expertise in
direct marketing and handling orders through catalogs and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Financial and Credit Services Group, the Federated unit that
handles credit-card operations for the company's stores and those
of some other retailers, is now supervising Fingerhut's credit
operations, management said.
</P>
<P>
   The problems do not affect Federated's core business of
department stores including Macy's, Bloomingdale's, The Bon Marche
and Rich's, said James Zimmerman, Federated's chairman and chief
executive officer. Those stores are performing well, except for
weaker sales lately in apparel, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Federated has annual sales of $17.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company is stepping up its debt collections, reducing the
size of credit lines and tightening initial granting of credit to
reduce exposure to bad debt, management said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are taking this situation very seriously,'' Zimmerman said.
''We believe we understand the problem, we know what caused it and
we are aggressively taking steps to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Federated said Fingerhut's credit delinquencies were caused by:
</P>
<P>
   - Implementing late-payment fees, with an inadequate provision
for write-offs.
</P>
<P>
   - Aggressive deferred-credit offerings for new customers.
</P>
<P>
   - Higher interest rates and increased gasoline prices that have
made it harder for low-income customers, who benefited from looser
credit availability in recent years, to meet credit obligations
now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
