<HEADLINE> Hatch, Leahy: Sens. Aren't Racist  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate Judiciary Committee's top
Republican branded as ''false and malicious'' recent allegations
that Senate Republicans are racist for holding up approval of
minority and female judge nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ''Has Congress really sunk so low?'' Judiciary Chairman Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as the committee approved the nomination of
Johnnie Rawlinson of Nevada, who is a black woman, for a 9th
Circuit Court of Appeals seat. Her nomination has been pending
since February.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlinson has been a federal judge in Las Vegas since 1998 and
is the first black woman in Nevada history to hold a position on
the U.S. District Court bench.
</P>
<P>
   The full Senate must still vote on the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Congressional Black Caucus leveled the
accusations against the GOP-controlled Senate on Wednesday. Judges
cannot be approved without first making it through Hatch's
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Judiciary Committee and the Senate consider judicial
nominees without regard to their race or gender,'' said Hatch, who
pointed out that 60 percent of African-American nominees have been
approved since he became chairman of the Judiciary Committee in
1995. ''Any contrary accusation or even suggestion is simply false
and malicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., defending Hatch, said he knows that
the committee chairman is neither racist or sexist. But the ranking
Democrat on the Judiciary Committee says the committee should
appoint more judges before the year is up.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a long way to go before we can think about resting on
any laurels,'' Leahy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Black Caucus is citing figures showing that,
as of last November, the Senate had confirmed 42 percent of
Clinton's white nominees but less than 18 percent of his black
nominees. Also, during last year's congressional session, senators
took two months longer to consider black nominees than they did
considering whites, and 65 days longer considering women than they
did men, the caucus said.
</P>
<P>
   They also want a black nominee approved for the 4th Circuit,
which covers South Carolina, North Carolina, Virginia, Maryland and
West Virginia. That circuit has never had a black judge, although
it has more black citizens than any other judicial circuit in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., has used his power as that state's
senator to block three North Carolinians from having their
nominations heard. He says the circuit has enough judges. The
caucus is now pushing Roger Gregory of Virginia for the seat, which
has been vacant for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the committee does not consider race and gender in
its decisions. However, he says that Justice Department figures
show that since January, 59 percent of minority nominees and 65
percent of female nominees have been approved. White males were
approved at a 64 percent rate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Minority nominees, female nominees and white male nominees are
being confirmed in nearly identical ratios,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Senate Judiciary Committee:
http://www.senate.gov/~judiciary/
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Black Caucus: http://www.house.gov/clyburn/cbc.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
