<HEADLINE> Leaders To Skip Peru Inauguration  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Colombia's president on Thursday became the
12th Latin leader to announce plans to skip the inauguration of
President Alberto Fujimori, who's battling charges that his
re-election was tainted.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian President Andres Pastrana's agenda is ''exceedingly
full,'' said Maria Cristina Zuleta, Colombia's ambassador to Peru.
She said Vice President Gustavo Bell will be sent in his place.
</P>
<P>
   The declined invitation follows charges from opposition forces
that Fujimori and his supporters waged an illegal campaign of dirty
tricks, intimidation and fraud to gain an unprecedented five-year
term.
</P>
<P>
   International election monitors say Peru's presidential election
failed to meet basic international standards for a fair and free
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Most Latin American presidents were loath to condemn Fujimori's
May 28 re-election victory over an opponent who boycotted the vote,
charging Fujimori planned to rig the result. Many of them now
appear to be distancing themselves from the authoritarian leader.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Mexico, Paraguay,
Uruguay, Costa Rica, Panama, El Salvador, Guatemala and Cuba have
excused themselves from Fujimori's swearing in, many citing
scheduling conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Nine Latin American presidents attended Fujimori's second term
inauguration in 1995. Five were there for his first term ceremony
in 1990. But as of Thursday, only the presidents of Ecuador and
Bolivia had confirmed that they will come to the new inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Since his re-election, Fujimori has pledged to negotiate with
his political rivals to improve Peru's damaged democracy with the
help of the Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
   Dominican Republic Foreign Minister Eduardo Latorre, who is
scheduled to take up residence in Peru in August as a special OAS
envoy, met this week with Fujimori and opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone with whom we have spoken, including President Alberto
Fujimori, recognizes the need to take action to fortify democratic
institutions in Peru,'' Latorre said before taking off from Lima's
international airport late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition parties, civic leaders and labor federations
still plan to launch three days of peaceful protests next week in
an attempt to disrupt Fujimori's swearing in.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has said that no state of emergency will be declared to
thwart the demonstrations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
