<TEXT>
<P>
	   MEDUSA, N.Y. (AP) - An 86-year-old man was critically injured
Thursday when a 2-year-old girl wriggled out of her car seat and
put a minivan into gear, causing it to roll 150 feet before hitting
the man, police said.
</P>
<P>
   George Dudley, an architect who worked on such projects as
Lincoln Center, Rockefeller Center and the Empire State Plaza,
suffered internal injuries, broken bones in his face and cuts,
according to Albany Medical Center Hospital spokesman Greg McGarry.
After surgery, he was in critical condition in the hospital's
intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Police said 27-year-old Pennie Chase parked at the Medusa
General Store to mail some letters and left the engine running in
the 1988 Plymouth Caravan. Her daughter managed to get free of the
car seat and put the van in gear. It rolled 150 feet across the
street and over Dudley, who was sitting in a lawn chair sketching.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley was pinned beneath the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the toddler was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   Chase was ticketed for leaving an unattended motor vehicle.
</P>
