<HEADLINE> Congress may reimburse Morris County agencies for protest cost  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - Morris County, site of a World Bank conference
in April that drew three days of protest, would receive $500,000 in
reimbursement from the federal government under proposals endorsed
Thursday by congressional committees.
</P>
<P>
   The protest, which attracted about 200 demonstrators the weekend
of March 31-April 2, led to nine arrests for charges that included
trespassing and failing to disperse. Officials estimated the cost
to state, county and local police and other agencies, would exceed
$500,000, much of that for overtime payments.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., and Rep. Rodney Frelinghuysen,
R-N.J., announced Thursday that the appropriations committees in
their respective chambers had approved more than $500,000 in
reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   The provisions are included in House and Senate appropriations
bills to fund the Treasury Department in 2001. If approved by both
houses, the treasury bill will go to President Clinton for his
signature.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg and Frelinghuysen, whose district includes much of
Morris County, said more than 740 officers from 46 local police
departments joined federal officers to protect conference
participants, local residents and property.
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers had told police that at least 500 protesters
could be expected at the Hamilton Park Conference Center in Florham
Park. The conference was sponsored by the World Bank, International
Monetary Fund and the Brookings Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was organized by a coalition of grass-roots groups
called the New Jersey/New York Mobilization for Global Justice. The
groups maintained that the World Bank and the IMF, charged with
improving life in developing countries, instead throws the
countries into debt while enriching corporations and degrading the
environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
