<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sentenced reduced for Vineland man after Supreme Court decision  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGETON, N.J. (AP) - A Vineland man whose sentence on a hate
crime conviction was overturned by the U.S. Supreme Court is
expected to be released soon.
</P>
<P>
   State Superior Court Judge Rushton H. Ridgway on Thursday
reduced the sentence for Charles C. Apprendi Jr. from 12 years to
seven in the wake of a June Supreme Court ruling that the finding
that Apprendi was motivated by bias was improperly made.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said, because of the Supreme Courts' decision, the
longer sentence for a bias crime had to be vacated.
</P>
<P>
   Apprendi, who is white, was arrested in December 1994 after
eight shots were fired into the home of a black family living in
his otherwise all-white neighborhood in Vineland. No one was
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Apprendi, 45, admitted to the shooting, and at first he told
police he wanted to send a message to the family that they did not
belong in the neighborhood. Later, he said he was pressured into
making a false statement, and that he had no racial intent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was criminal mischief, that's all it was,'' he said outside
court Thursday, adding that he was under the influence of drugs and
alcohol at the time.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's hate-crime law bans acts of racial or ethnic
intimidation, such as burning crosses or painting swastikas. It
provides stiffer sentences for such crimes as assault and
harassment if the defendant acted with a ''purpose to intimidate''
because of factors such as race, sex or religion.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled that a jury - not a judge alone - must
decide when bias is the motive behind a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also said in such cases, the highest legal standard
- whether prosecutors offered proof beyond a reasonable doubt -
must be used. In imposing Apprendi's original sentence, the judge
said prosecutors showed by a ''preponderance of the evidence'' that
Apprendi's act was racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Ridgway reduced the sentence to seven years for weapons
violations and for possession of a bomb, which was found in
Apprendi's house.
</P>
<P>
   Apprendi already has served five years and seven months in
prison and halfway houses. His lawyer, Joseph D. O'Neill, said
Thursday that he would ask the state Department of Corrections to
release his client.
</P>
<P>
   Victim Mattie Harrell called his sentence ''a slap on the
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she will seek a restraining order barring Apprendi from
coming near her family or her home, which is less than 2 miles from
where he will live with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Cumberland County Prosecutor Arthur Marchand said he will seek
that as a condition of Apprendi's parole. ''I think it's a fair
request,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell said with Apprendi's release imminent, ''I feel like the
horror is about to begin all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrell said one of the bullets came through her son's bedroom
and lodged in a hallway. Michael, 14, is still afraid to sleep in
his room, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''How do I explain to him that he has nothing to worry about,''
she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I try to teach my children that we live in a country of
fairness and discipline,'' she said. ''If someone hurts you, they
will be punished for their actions. But now I feel I have to eat my
own words.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For current Supreme Court decisions:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.supremecourtus.gov
</P>
<P>
   http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
