<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge clears man convicted of 'bombing' ex-employer's computer programs </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A federal judge has thrown out a guilty
verdict against an industrial designer convicted of leaving his
ex-employer a computer ''bomb'' that erased critical programs.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge William H. Walls ruled that a juror who
contacted him after the trial was unfairly tainted because she
heard about an unrelated computer problem, the ''Love Bug'' virus,
after deliberations started, a prosecutor and defense lawyer said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Assistant U.S. Attorney V. Grady O'Malley, said
Thursday that the ruling, issued July 14 from the bench, would be
appealed to the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just hearing inadvertently about the 'Love Bug,' which is
really an insignificant piece of information, does not measure up
to what the 3rd Circuit has found to be sufficient to overturn a
verdict,'' O'Malley said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy A. Lloyd is believed to be the first person to stand
trial under a new federal computer sabotage law.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Edward J. Crisonino, said that in 16 years as a
defense attorney this was the first case in which a trial judge
reversed a jury verdict against one of his clients.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's pretty rare,'' Crisonino said. ''It's very lucky on Mr.
Lloyd's part that the woman picked up the phone and called the
judge because we would never have known about it otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd, 37, of New Castle, Del. was convicted May 9 and faced up
to five years in prison, a fine of up to $250,000, and an order of
restitution at sentencing, which was scheduled for July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities say Lloyd's actions caused Omega Engineering
Corp. to lose more than $10 million in sales, damage and lost
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Omega is based in Stamford, Conn., and Lloyd worked at the
office in Bridgeport, N.J. The company produces sophisticated
measuring devices and control equipment, including temperature
controls used by NASA rockets and Navy submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd was convicted of intentionally damaging a computer, but
acquitted of the other charge he faced, taking about $50,000 of
Omega computer hardware and software to his home.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict came after 12 hours of deliberations over three days
following a three-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Gaudin, who covered the trial for Network World magazine,
said such cases are rare. ''It's pretty hard because companies
don't want to stand up and wave their hands and say, 'We've been
hit,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ''It's a concern for any company out there
now, because so much of a company's enterprise is dependent on its
network,'' Gaudin said.
</P>
<P>
   The juror's name has not been made public, Crisonino said. She
called the judge several days after the verdict and said she heard
about the virus during a weekend break, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The information contributed to her guilty vote because it helped
her realize that physical access to a computer system was not
essential to cause a crash, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I argued it was a taint because it was evidence that was not
presented to the jury, and we couldn't counter it,'' Crisonino
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd was Omega's file system administrator in August 1995, when
he was demoted. He began testing the computer bomb in February
1996, and was fired July 10, 1996, after 11 years with the company,
prosecutors said showed.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty days later, the bomb was unleashed as planned, deleting
and purging Omega's most critical manufacturing programs,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd did not testify at his trial. His defense maintained that
Lloyd did not cause the crash and that it is impossible to
determine who did, Crisonino said.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd remains under house arrest, but is allowed to travel daily
to do computer work at a Delaware machine shop, his lawyer said.
The lawyer said he did not know the company's name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-20-00 1920 </TRAILER>
