<HEADLINE> Clinton meeting with taxi driver president  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton said Thursday she
supports spending federal money on security partitions for New York
City's livery cabs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the comments on her way to a meeting with Fernando
Mateo, president of the New York State Federation of Taxi Drivers.
Ten livery cab drivers have been killed in New York City since
January.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am concerned about the real danger that livery cab drivers
find themselves in New York and the number that have been murdered
in cold blood this past year,'' Clinton told The Associated Press
in a telephone interview Thursday. ''We've got to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she supports legislation sponsored by Sen.
Charles Schumer, D-N.Y, and Rep. Jose Serrano, D-Bronx, that would
provide $600,000 in federal money for the purchase of bulletproof
partitions.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki signed legislation earlier this year
increasing the penalties for violence against cabbies. The law adds
three to five years to the sentences of anyone convicted of
attacking cab drivers.
</P>
<P>
   New York police earlier this year formed a task force to deal
with cab driver killings, and the city now requires all drivers to
install either partitions or security cameras in their cars.
</P>
