<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge issues preliminary injunction on Princeton smoking ban  </HEADLINE>
By DERRICK HENRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A judge in New Jersey has blocked
enforcement of the state's toughest smoking ban and has given
parties in the case a week to supplement the arguments they
presented in court on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia-based National Smokers Alliance and three Princeton
bars and restaurants filed the lawsuit June 8, saying the Princeton
Regional Health Commission didn't have the authority to enact the
ban, which would restrict smoking to homes, cigar shops or
outdoors. Violators would face fines from $100 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''This commission strayed from the law,'' said Ross A. Lewin, a
Princeton attorney representing the smokers alliance and the bars
and restaurants. In court, Lewin presented to Superior Court Judge
Linda R. Feinberg excerpts from five state statutes that said
groups such as the Princeton Regional Health Commission may only
suggest - and not mandate - guidelines about concerns such as
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But Feinberg told Lewin, ''I don't think you can dispose of this
whole case on that particular condition. This case is more complex
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Before issuing the preliminary injunction, Feinberg also said
the list of statutes to which Lewin referred ''isn't as ironclad as
the plaintiffs would have you believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, lawyers representing the Princeton Regional Health
Commission said the commission's move was legal because people have
a right to be free from secondhand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had the authority to enact the ban based on local
concerns about fire safety, said Robert J. Conroy, one of the
lawyers representing the commission and a coalition of 45 groups,
including the American Cancer Society and the Medical Society of
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a long history of local rule in New Jersey,'' Conroy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Conroy, who practices in Bridgewater, said in the past it has
been the intent of the Legislature to allow municipalities to enact
such ordinances, thus making the commission's actions legal.
</P>
<P>
   Feinberg also quizzed the defense lawyers about exceptions to
the ordinance, which in includes private clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told defense lawyers to write a brief elaborating on
those exceptions. She also asked if the state's smoking statute
intended for municipalities to regulate establishments listed in
the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it (the case) is going to have implications statewide
because other towns are dealing with the same concerns,'' said
Karen L. Cayci, a Princeton lawyer who also is representing the
commission and the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the ban took exception to legal arguments against
it. They said they are more concerned with the effects of
secondhand smoke on people's health.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Carlson, executive director of New Jersey Group Against
Smoking Pollution, or GASP, said, ''We really want some protection
for our health, for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   One supporter explained the need for defending the ban with a
legal technicality.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're arguing within the points of a law that doesn't have the
benefit of scientific evidence,'' said Tara Fredreck, a spokeswoman
with the American Cancer Society Eastern Division. ''Really, the
only option for us is to go on the fire safety issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy, one of the defense lawyers, said if the smoking ban is
thrown out, there could be a call for statewide legislation further
restricting where smoking can take place.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the citizens of this state will hold their legislators
accountable because they failed to act,'' Conroy said.
</P>
<P>
   Feinberg didn't set a new hearing date. She instead told lawyers
to file supplemental briefs by July 28.
</P>
<P>
   Other New Jersey towns, including Glassboro, Highland Park,
Lawrence Township, Marlboro, Secaucus and South Brunswick, restrict
smoking in a variety of sites, but none has a ban as sweeping as
Princeton's.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.speakup.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cancer.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.msnj.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.monmouth.com/~hpkatseff/njgasp/
</P>
</TEXT>
