<HEADLINE> Police arrest man in concrete attack  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A 35-year-old man was arrested for allegedly
attacking an aspiring social worker with a 5-pound chunk of
concrete as she left a Manhattan church, police said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Police stopped Bently Louis Grant four days after the attack on
Tiffany Goldberg because he fit the description of the man they
were looking for, but let him go because there wasn't enough
evidence to hold him, said Commissioner Howard Safir.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said a witness to the attack later picked Grant's picture
out of a photo lineup. Officers arrested him in Brooklyn's Prospect
Park late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At least one witness also picked Grant out of an in-person
lineup. The suspect is believed to be homeless, with no known
criminal record, Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, 25, suffered a cracked skull after an attacker sneaked
up behind her on July 9 and hit her with a piece of pavement. The
assailant allegedly tried to rob her before running away.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, a native of Madison, Wis., also suffered chipped
teeth, a black eye, cuts and bruises when she fell.
</P>
<P>
   She had just left Marble Collegiate Presbyterian Church on 29th
Street and Park Avenue, where she sings in the gospel choir, when
she was hit.
</P>
<P>
   An off-duty firefighter, Lt. Jimmy Hurley, was driving by. He
gave up his chase of the attacker when he saw how badly Goldberg
was bleeding. He wrapped a white T-shirt around her head and held
her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Police said earlier that descriptions of the attacker appeared
to match that of a homeless man who frequented the neighborhood; a
city shelter is about two blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said Grant admitted to the crime in interviews with
police, and that the suspect would face charges of attempted murder
in the second degree, first-degree assault, and criminal possession
of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate incident on Wednesday night, Anthony Gonsalves,
43, of Trumbull, Conn., had his right arm partially severed when a
2-foot-long concrete slab was thrown through his laundry truck
windshield from a Bronx highway overpass. Doctors at Bellevue
Hospital, where he was listed in critical but stable condition,
were working to reattach the arm.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Nicole Barrett, then 27, was hit on the head with
a paving brick in midtown Manhattan while walking to work. She
underwent two brain operations and has returned to her family's
home in Athens, Texas, for rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a 30-year-old Queens woman was hit with a brick and
robbed.
</P>
</TEXT>
