<HEADLINE> Israelis, Palestinians Voice Cases  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Supporters and opponents of the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders stepped forward Thursday to make their cases
known before the two sides go back to the negotiating table at Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish settlers commemorated a traditional fast day that recalls
the destruction of ancient Jerusalem by accusing Prime Minister
Ehud Barak of giving up the holy city in modern times. Palestinians
demonstrated urging Yasser Arafat to stand firm.
</P>
<P>
   At President Clinton's urging, the leaders remained at the
retreat near Washington for the weekend, although nine days of
intensive talks aimed at producing a permanent peace accord failed.
Talks are expected to resume when Clinton returns from an economic
summit next week.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli media said the sides were using the break to study
American proposals aimed at unraveling the knottiest disagreements,
over Jerusalem, borders and refugees.
</P>
<P>
   All sides were planning major demonstrations over the weekend.
Peace activists planned a prayer vigil by the Western Wall in
Jerusalem's Old City on Friday. A central square in Tel Aviv is to
be the scene of a mass demonstration against Barak Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this overheated political culture, the rhetoric achieved
an unprecedented apocalyptic tone.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon, a close associate of Barak, warned
of the grim alternatives to a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''An explosion in the talks can lead to other explosions which
might lead to bloodshed,'' Ramon told Israel's army radio.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish settlers also said they were preparing for Palestinian
violence if the summit failed.
</P>
<P>
   Settler leader Pinhas Wallerstein said his settlement recently
purchased nightvision equipment and telescopes for weapons. He is
also requesting additional bullet proof vests for settlement
security guards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone understands Arafat wants a war between us and we need
to prepare ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The army confirmed that it had been providing extra training to
reserves soldiers who live on the settlements. Army chief of staff
Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz has said he fears an intensification of
violence if the talks fail.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians decried such warnings as provocative -- but
echoed them in their own predictions of what failure would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the summit fails, we will enter a black era in the history
of peace process,'' said Communications Minister Imad Fallouji.
''And if we face any Israeli challenges, we are ready and all our
options are open.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Hamas, a militant Islamic group opposed to the
