<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Announces Business Initiatives  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations on Thursday announced
the first members of a new corporate effort to promote human rights
and environmental standards in business.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes companies such as Nike and Shell, which have
been criticized for abuses overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights and environmental groups which have questioned the
growing U.N.-business affiliation immediately denounced the
so-called ''Global Compact,'' saying it could allow companies to
use the U.N. flag to clean their tarnished public images.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan launched the ''Global Compact'' in
January 1999, asking corporations to commit themselves to nine key
principles, including pledges to protect human rights, uphold the
rights of workers to unionize, eliminate child labor and develop
environmentally friendly technologies.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Annan warned that the principles were necessary to
uphold because corporations risked a backlash from those who
weren't benefitting from globalization -- a backlash which has since
borne out in protests in Seattle and elsewhere at global trade
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Next Wednesday, the United Nations will convene the first
meeting of the participants of the new partnership, which has
enlisted nearly 50 companies as well as labor organizations and
human rights groups such as Amnesty International and Lawyers
Committee for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the corporations will be asked to post examples of
progress they have made in implementing the nine principles on a
special U.N. website. The labor and human rights members of the
partnerships will be able to respond to those initiatives on the
same site.
</P>
<P>
   John Ruggie, Annan's special adviser, said this ''structured
dialogue'' between corporations and labor and human rights groups
could be a powerful force for change.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course you can't rule out anything, but I would be very
surprised if any one of these companies attempted to do a snowjob
on us,'' Ruggie told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Posner, executive director of Lawyers Committee for
Human Rights, said his organization had decided to join the
parnership reasoning that if corporations were willing to show up,
''we need to be there to say these are the things we think you need
to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a coalition of environmental groups including
Greenpeace International and human rights organizations from the
developing world sent a letter to Annan on Thursday asking that he
reconsider the ''Global Compact'' and instead focus on establishing
a binding legal framework to oversee the conduct of multinational
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Asking corporations to sign a vague statement ''draws attention
away from the need for more substantial action to hold corporations
accountable for their behavior,'' said the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Karliner, executive director of Transnational Resource
and Action Center, one of the letter's co-signers, said it was
particularly appalling that the first parners in the ''Global
Compact'' had such questionable records.
</P>
<P>
   Nike Inc., for example, has been targeted by labor organizations
for conditions at its factories in Asia. Shell has been criticized
for environmental degradation around its oil fields in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Kidd, vice president of corporate responsibility at Nike
said Nike wasn't looking for public relations points, noting that
labor groups were part of the U.N. forum. He said Nike was merely
looking to improve conditions at its plants.
</P>
<P>
   ''One thing we've learned the hard way is the sooner you start
talking about these issues the sooner you get solutions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Shell weren't answered Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 2022 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000720.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GAO: Parks Put Costs Before Safety  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The wildfire that burned hundreds of homes in
Los Alamos, N.M., raged out of control in part because National
Park Service officials did not use bulldozers and chainsaws to
contain the blaze, congressional investigators reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office suggested the Park Service revise
its policy that firefighting efforts be the cheapest and least
environmentally damaging.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the Park Service ''generally agreed'' with the
recommendation. It was not immediately clear whether the agency
would change its policy. Park Service spokesmen did not return
telephone messages left Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service set a fire on May 4 to clear underbrush in
Bandelier National Monument. When that fire started getting out of
control, Park Service officials chose to set other fires to try to
contain it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the containment fires got out of control, becoming the
Cerro Grande fire that charred nearly 48,000 acres, destroyed more
than 200 homes and burned parts of the Los Alamos National
Laboratory, America's first nuclear weapons lab. Damage estimates
have ranged as high as $1 billion; President Clinton signed a $661
million fire compensation package last week.
</P>
<P>
   Using chainsaws and bulldozers to make a fire break ''was not
chosen because it would have been inconsistent with Park Service
policy calling for resource damage to be minimized,'' said the
report written by environmental expert Barry Hill of the GAO, the
investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''The existing Park Service policy requiring fire managers to
protect resources while trying to suppress a wildfire should be
revised in instances like Cerro Grande,'' Hill wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''In these cases, where the threat of a prescribed fire's
getting out of control poses direct and serious public safety
risks, there should be no question that fire suppression should be
the top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service has halted all prescribed fires in the West
because of the New Mexico fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   Bandelier Superintendent Roy Weaver retired this month and
apologized to Los Alamos citizens for approving the original fire.
Park Service officials have not determined whether anyone will be
disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Park Service site on Cerro Grande fire:
http://www.nps.gov/band/fire.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 2027 </TRAILER>
