<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shore landmark's renovations finally completed -- after 30 years  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARGATE, N.J. (AP) - Lucy the Elephant is as good as new. Or as
good as a six-story, 119-year-old wooden elephant gets.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years to the day after the rotting Victorian-era oddity
was moved to its current location, city officials and members of
the Save Lucy Committee gathered Thursday to pull the curtain on
the final phase of more than $1 million in renovations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Finally, this project has ended,'' said Margaret Westfield,
one of the architects who worked on the renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1881 by real estate mogul James Lafferty as a gimmick
to attract buyers to what was then South Atlantic City, Lucy the
Elephant served - at various times - as a hotel, a summer cottage
and a tavern before being converted into a full-time tourist
attraction in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   It fell into disrepair in the 1960s, however, and had
deteriorated badly when, in 1969, a group of residents organized
the Save Lucy Committee to spare it from the wrecking ball. On July
20, 1970, the elephant was moved two blocks to its current location
on Decatur Avenue and the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, more than $1 million - in private donations and
historic preservation grants - has been spent to repair and
maintain the building. In 1997, it was designated a National
Historic Landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The latest phase of work, which cost $260,000, restored the
inside of the elephant, replacing the dilapidated wooden beams with
new hardwood floors, recessed ceiling lights and varnished
stairways and banisters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank you, thank you, thank you, a million times,'' beamed
Josephine Harron, president of nonprofit committee, who thanked
supporters during a 15-minute ceremony held beneath the giant
tusks.
</P>
<P>
   One first-time visitor was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely worth saving,'' said Michael Whalan, 48, of
Bailey's Crossroads, Va., as he descended the stairs in the
elephant's right rear foot, at the end of a tour. ''It's a little
bit silly, but it's fun. It's better-spent money than a lot of the
things they spend money on, like congressional junkets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-20-00 2038 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
