<HEADLINE> Former casino security guard on trial in death of panhandler  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - A coroner's investigator testified
Thursday that there were visible signs of trauma when she arrived
to examine the body of an unruly gambler who was allegedly beaten
to death by a casino security guard.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petty, 37, of Galloway Township is accused of aggravated
manslaughter and four counts of witness tampering in the Sept. 8,
1998 death of Hue To, 25, of Plainfield.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say To was ejected from the casino for panhandling
near a poker table. Petty allegedly beat him to death after taking
him into an office at Trump Plaza Hotel &AMP; Casino.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses say the 6-foot-1 inch, 240-pound Petty kicked the
5-foot-1 inch To, who weighed about 100 pounds, and threw him into
a door.
</P>
<P>
   The coroner's investigator, H. Louise Houseman, told jurors that
To's body had contusions on the abdomen, sternum, elbow and eyes
when she first saw it at Atlantic City Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a fellow former Trump Plaza guard testified that
she heard a crash from the room where Petty and To were, and that
another guard told her the man had died.
</P>
<P>
   ''She said, 'He's dead. Mark killed him,''' said Lisa Marie
Johnson, who is now an Atlantic County corrections officer. ''She
said that (Petty) kicked him like a football.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty is charged with persuading four other guards to lie for
him to cover up the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Waldron, 51, of Egg Harbor Township, an investigator for
Trump Plaza, also is charged with witness tampering. She threatened
the four, warning them not to tell the truth about what happened
because it would send Petty to jail and result in their firings,
according to First Assistant Prosecutor Ellen Loughney.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Petty faces 10 to 30 years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-20-00 2040 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000720.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court dismisses Silver's suit vs. Pataki vetoes  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan appeals court Thursday threw out a
legal challenge to Gov. George Pataki's right to exercise the
line-item veto on 55 items in the 1998-99 state budget sent him by
the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Division, in a decision the judges called
unprecedented, ruled 3-2 that Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, the
Manhattan Democrat who filed the lawsuit, did not have standing to
challenge Pataki's vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing a lower court's January 1999 ruling, the majority
found that nothing in the state constitution gives the Speaker of
the Assembly the duty or the power to seek judicial review of
gubernatorial actions.
</P>
<P>
   At issue were the governor's vetoes of ''non-appropriations''
parts of the state budget. Pataki has line-item veto authority over
individual budget appropriations, and he vetoed some $1.6 billion
in legislative spending.
</P>
<P>
   Silver argued on behalf of the Assembly's Democratic majority
that Pataki abused his power by also deleting language pertaining
to the allocations and deciding unilaterally how the funds would be
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said late Thursday that ''in all likelihood the case will
be decided by the Court of Appeals,'' the state's highest court. He
noted that two Appellate Division judges dissented and agreed with
the lower court.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a remark by the lower court judge, Justice Edward Lehner
of State Supreme Court in Manhattan, Silver said ''who better than
the Speaker to challenge the action's of the state's chief
executive?''
</P>
<P>
   ''We would have anarchy if the governor could do just anything
without the usual checks and balances,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   But the appellate majority disagreed. They pointed to a
30-year-old case that held ''legislators, as legislators, are
unable to bring disputes regarding budgetary differences with the
governor into a court.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehner, a Democrat, noted the earlier decision but refused to
follow its reasoning, saying that if he did it would let Pataki
escape any ''judicial scrutiny'' of his vetoes, which is contrary
to the intent of other rulings.
</P>
<P>
   The majority, in a decision written by Justice John T. Buckley,
also said that allowing the speaker to sue the governor would
confer on him an authority that is contrary to the letter and
spirit of separate governmental powers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Buckley wrote, allowing such a precedent ''will needlessly
propel the judiciary into future political conflicts.'' He scolded
the dissenters for ignoring prior rulings that mostly kept the
courts out of political fights.
</P>
<P>
   ''Logic and common sense counsel judicial abstinence, or at
least restraint, when a political dispute beckons, as this does,''
Buckley wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
