<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York GOP boss: Pataki is on Bush's short list ... maybe  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki is on Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush's short list of possible
running mates, New York's GOP chairman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But less than an hour later, and after calls went out to Pataki
and the Bush campaign for comment, party leader William Powers
backtracked and said he really didn't know who was on the list.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at the state Republican Party headquarters,
Powers said it was his understanding that the Texas governor was
considering three potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's on the short list,'' Powers said when asked about Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he knew that, the state chairman smiled and said,
''Good sources.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a subsequent interview, Powers said he had ''no inside
information'' about Bush's deliberations over a running mate and
that his earlier comments were based largely ''on my speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, Pataki brushed off speculation Thursday that his
attendance at a fund-raiser for members of the California Assembly
signaled he is a serious vice presidential contender. California
and New York are key electoral states.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been out to California time and again to make speeches to
different political organizations, different civic organizations,''
he said shortly after a speech to members of the Lincoln Club of
Orange County. ''This has been set up for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's West Coast appearance came just as Bush told
reporters he was close to making a decision. Pataki is one of
several people said to be under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki could help Bush carry a state that hasn't been won by a
Republican presidential contender since Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pataki acknowledged he had met with Bush in recent
days, he refused to discuss details of their discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any conversations I may or may not have had with Gov. Bush
that are private are private,'' he said. ''I'm not speculating on
what may or may not happen, or what I may or may not do if
something may or may not have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said Bush has made it
clear that only his closest advisers know who is on his short list
of possible running mates.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Powers said he had first heard last week
of Pataki's inclusion on Bush's short list of possible running
mates. The state party chairman noted that he had been in Texas
last week meeting with Bush campaign officials, but refused to say
if that is where his information about Pataki came from.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at his news conference, Powers was coy about Pataki's
possible inclusion on the list, telling reporters at one point that
he based his statement on ''good instincts.'' He later amended that
to ''good sources.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP leader said that while he would like to see Pataki as
Bush's running mate and felt the New York governor could help a
Bush-led ticket in New York and nationally, it wasn't clear who
Bush would pick.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he is unpredictable when it comes to something like
that,'' Powers said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is one of several names that have cropped up in recent
days as possible Bush running mates, but the Texas governor has
said that only he, his wife and his vice presidential search team
leader, former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, know who is really
under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The New York governor met privately with Bush last Friday in New
Jersey and later in Manhattan to discuss the vice presidency and
other issues. Pataki has refused to talk about his discussions with
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A potential stumbling block for Pataki when it comes to a spot
on the GOP ticket is his record as an abortion rights supporter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-20-00 2050 </TRAILER>
