<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Jersey attorney general sues Worldcom over ads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey is one of six states suing
long-distance carrier WorldCom Inc., alleging it deceives customers
in its advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John J. Farmer sued the Clinton, Miss.-based
company, which changed its name earlier this year from MCI
WorldCom, over its television and direct-mail ads that tell
consumers they will pay only 5 cents per minute for long-distance
service. He claims that rates are much higher due to hidden costs.
</P>
<P>
   He also accused the company of switching customers to WorldCom
without their consent, a practice known as ''slamming.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Companies advertising and doing business in New Jersey must do
so truthfully,'' Farmer said. ''The state will step in whenever are
wherever our laws are not obeyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer said the company's ''Five Cents Everyday'' program is not
available for toll calls made within New Jersey and is only
available from 7 p.m. to 6:59 a.m., but those facts were not
adequately disclosed to customers.
</P>
<P>
   He and other attorneys general also note the plan comes with a
service fee of $4.95 per month, a minimum long-distance charge of
$5, a carrier access charge of $1.46, and a federal fee of 7.2
percent of all long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for WorldCom said the company does not comment on
pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom is a global telecommunications company with revenue of
more than $30 billion and operations in more than 65 countries.
</P>
<P>
   A few states sued AT&AMP;T and Sprint over their promotions for
similar offers.
</P>
<P>
   The other states filing lawsuits Thursday were California,
Connecticut, Missouri, Minnesota and Maine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
