<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechens Said To Step Up Attacks  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Chechen rebels have intensified their
attacks on Russian troops in the past week in order to embarrass
Moscow at a high-profile international summit this weekend, a top
general said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Just since Wednesday, the guerrilla fighters killed seven
Russian soldiers and wounded 12 others with mines, sniper rifles
and roadside ambushes, the military command said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported that a troop
convoy came under attack just outside the Chechen capital of
Grozny. There was no immediate word on casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Russia for months has insisted that the rebels are on the verge
of defeat, but the guerrillas' hit-and-run attacks show they can
still inflict significant harm on the larger and better-equipped
Russian forces.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fighters become active when important political events are
expected in the international arena,'' deputy head of the general
staff Gen. Valery Manilov told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin will attend the Group of Eight summit,
which includes the world's wealthiest democracies, this weekend in
Okinawa, Japan. His talks with other leaders there are expected to
focus on Russian debt, but also touch on criticism of Russia's
conduct in the 11-month-long war.
</P>
<P>
   Western governments and human-rights groups have repeatedly
criticized Russia for indiscriminately killing civilians in the
offensive and for alleged human-rights violations including summary
executions and rapes.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels attacked Russian positions 63 times in the past week,
Manilov said, about double the rate of previous weeks. Russian
forces lost 25 dead and 74 wounded in the last week, Manilov said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the rebels want world leaders to understand the war goes
on, and that they ''still exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The skilled guerrillas traditionally prefer summer offensives
against Russian positions, when they can take advantage of thick
greenery in forests on the mountain slopes for cover, and can
bivouac easily in the wild areas in the warm weather.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of rebels saying their actions this week
were linked with the summit.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview released last week, Chechen President Aslan
Maskhadov accused the international community of failing to
pressure Russia into negotiating a settlement, but did not mention
the Okinawa summit.
</P>
<P>
   Putin promised a quick victory when troops moved into Chechnya
last September, but the conflict has long since bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   Manilov, meanwhile, said the military will take countermeasures
to the stepped-up attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should react, and, as we say, carry out prophylactic
measures,'' to prevent attacks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This has traditionally meant police searches for alleged rebels
in Chechen villages near where attacks took place.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which withdrew its forces from Chechnya after a 1994-96
war, sent ground troops back in last September, following weeks of
airstrikes. The Kremlin said the renewed offensive was necessary
after Chechen-based rebels twice invaded the neighboring region of
Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also blames Chechen militants for a series of September
apartment bombings that killed some 300 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 2104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
