<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Puerto Rican Lawyer Given 5 Years  </HEADLINE>
By MANUEL E. RIVERA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- A prominent lawyer was sentenced
Thursday to five years in jail for conspiring to steal $2.2 million
in U.S. funding meant for AIDS patients in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Dubon Otero, who was convicted of fraud in February, was
also ordered to repay $1.5 million stolen from the now-defunct San
Juan AIDS Institute as well as a fine of $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dubon's lawyer, David Roman, immediately said he would appeal
the sentence, calling it ''unjust and disproportionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubon, 65, was legal adviser for the institute and served on its
board, which received about $15 million from the Ryan White
Foundation, the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation and the U.S. Health
Department before it folded in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he decided on the maximum penalty because Dubon
was one of the masterminds and had destroyed documents in an
attempt to avoid prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Fuste sentenced the institute's operations
manager, pharmacist Jeannette Sotomayor, to three years and 10
months imprisonment. She was ordered to repay the nearly $36,000
she had the institute pay in wages to her personal housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen institute officials have been convicted in the case --
found guilty of diverting funds for personal use and political
campaigns between 1988 and 1994. Most pleaded guilty. Dubon was the
last to be sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal rocked this U.S. territory's government and forced
Gov. Pedro Rossello and former San Juan Mayor Hector Luis Acevedo
to take the stand to deny witnesses' allegations that they accepted
part of the stolen money. Both denied the claims and neither was
charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's director, Cuban Dr. Yamil Kouri, got the
toughest sentence of 14 years in prison. He was fined $17,500 and
ordered to pay back $1.3 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
