<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warner Reports to Rams Camp  </HEADLINE>
By R.B. FALLSTROM
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACOMB, Ill. (AP) -- Kurt Warner is not interested in contract
leverage.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL MVP reported to the Super Bowl champion St. Louis Rams'
training camp Thursday, a day before the first full-squad workout,
without a contract. The Rams were unable to come to an agreement on
a long-term deal before camp, so the quarterback said he'd sign a
tender offer for $358,000, the minimum for a veteran with two
years' experience, for now so that he could practice with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Two-a-day workouts begin Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to miss anything,'' Warner said. ''That's why I
came here, to practice from Day 1 and show my teammates that I
wanted to be here. I will definitely sign something so I can be out
there to practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner threw 42 touchdown passes last year in his first season
as a starter, after beginning training camp as an unknown
third-stringer. Before last year, he had made his mark only in NFL
Europe and Arena Football.
</P>
<P>
   Warner said his agent, Mark Bartelstein, advised him not to
report.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say I wanted to make sure he understood all the risks
that were involved,'' Bartelstein said. ''What he's doing, to me,
it's unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's basically trusting that this thing will be done, and
that's the way he's run his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did he do it?
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of my love of the game and my responsibility to this
team and my teammates and coaches outweighs everything else,''
Warner said. ''I definitely want to take care of my family, but I
realize why I'm here. It's something I felt I had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner said his decision had nothing to do with the state of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope we're close; it seems like we're close,'' he said.
''But you know when you're negotiating some things that seem like
they're close are a long ways away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams and Bartelstein have discussed four-, five- and
seven-year deals, but Bartelstein said it's all fallen short.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're talking about the MVP of the league,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Warner said he wasn't worried about the potential risks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel this is what I'm all about, and this is more important
to me than everything else,'' Warner said. ''Hopefully it all gets
all worked out, but this is more important to me right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams also signed first-round pick Trung Canidate, a running
back from Arizona, to a five-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Canidate, expected to practice Friday, set a school
single-season record last year with 1,602 yards, and averaged 6.3
yards per carry with 11 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really glad that we've got him for the first practice,''
coach Mike Martz said. ''Any rookie that misses any playing time,
it's magnified considerably. They get behind the 8-ball and spend
all year trying to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams also signed third-round pick John St. Clair, a center
from Virginia. St. Clair signed Thursday afternoon and showed up at
the Rams' high-rise dormitory about 8:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''Luckily, everything worked out,'' St. Clair said. ''I don't
want to miss any camp. You never want to be behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 2136 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000720.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer wants charges against teacher dismissed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.Y. (AP) - The lawyer for a teacher accused of
videotaping his kindergarten students as they undressed wants the
charges dropped because the state's voyeur laws do not cover such
an act.
</P>
<P>
   Michael S. Dorrington, 26, of Geneva, was charged with five
counts of endangering the welfare of a child last month. Police
said Dorrington hid a video camera in a storage closet in his
classroom, then told five girls to go inside and change into
bathing suits as part of ''Water Fun Day'' at Lincoln Elementary
School.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Dorrington later dropped the camera and brought it
to a repair shop. When the repairman fixed the camera and viewed
the tape, he called police.
</P>
<P>
   Geneva lawyer Michael Roulan on Wednesday said the state's only
law against video voyeurism applies to owners or managers
videotaping patrons, guests or employees in bathrooms, changing
rooms or any other private area of a business or other
profit-making establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Roulan also said that since Dorrington never thought the tape
would become public, there was no injury to the girls who were
taped.
</P>
<P>
   ''No logical argument can be made that any of these students
were ever in a danger which would likely be injurious to them or to
their mental health,'' said Roulan. ''The conduct that is
attributable to Mr. Dorrington cannot be said to be such that he
knowingly thought that this tape would become public.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents of the five young girls who were videotaped said the
motion for dismissal is a ''slap in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Village Justice Bruce Chambers ordered Dorrington to return to
court Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Newark is 27 miles east of Rochester.	   
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-20-00 2138 </TRAILER>
