<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Big Brother' Guest Kicked Out  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The first of 10 people whose lives are being
followed by dozens of television cameras in the CBS ''Big Brother''
house was kicked out Thursday -- and he certainly wasn't broken up
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes! Yes!'' William said when he learned, on live TV, that
viewers had given him the boot.
</P>
<P>
   William, a 27-year-old youth counselor from Philadelphia, was a
provocateur who spent much of his two weeks fighting with fellow
residents. He said later that it was ''too prissy'' and ''I'm used
to playing roughhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS has been airing ''Big Brother'' five nights a week, and will
add another night next week as the series continues through late
September. The series that follows the social experiment of putting
strangers in a wired house has garnered mediocre ratings and
criticism that it's too dull.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little slow inside the house, too.
</P>
<P>
   William admitted that he tried to pull a prank on his fellow
residents -- pretending they'd been ordered to rearrange the
furniture -- because ''I was going crazy with the boringness.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's only so much reading you can do, only so much
weightlifting ... I thought I'd work on some people's heads,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also sabotaged a challenge by deliberately losing a game that
his housemates were playing to win more supplies, and was involved
in an expletive-laden, racially tense shouting match with Eddie, a
college student.
</P>
<P>
   Neither viewers nor his fellow residents appreciated it. Along
with Jordan, a 26-year-old former stripper, he was one of two
people nominated by the housemates to be expelled. Viewers chose
between them by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   William was voted out by a nearly three-to-one margin. CBS would
not divulge how many people voted.
</P>
<P>
   He said later he ''wouldn't change a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm used to being number one -- either first one out or last
one out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS ''Early Show'' newsreader Julie Chen anchored the one-hour
live show. The CBS News employee has been criticized for playing an
entertainment role, most recently when her counterpart on NBC's
''Today'' show, Ann Curry, told TV critics Wednesday, ''I would not
have chosen to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last five minutes, Chen brought up a New York Daily News
report that said William, who also goes by the name Hiram Ashantee,
is a follower of ousted Nation of Islam leader Khalid Abdul
Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was a member of the New Black Panther Party for
Self-Defense and complained that Chen gave him only a brief
commercial break to look over the Daily News story and comment on
it.
</P>
<P>
   After he learned he was leaving, William picked up his bags and
left the house without saying goodbye. That's when most of the
people he had spent two weeks with appeared at the doorway to watch
him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh,'' he said. ''Later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 2153 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
