<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fox Hires Risk Management Firm  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The network that pioneered the reality
TV genre doesn't quite trust itself after the ''Who Wants to Marry
a Multimillionaire'' disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has hired Price Waterhouse as a ''risk management firm'' to
advise whether some future reality shows cross the boundaries of
bad taste, network head Sandy Grushow said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company will conduct background checks of reality show
participants and even watch over production, Grushow said.
</P>
<P>
   Grushow is trying to distance Fox from cheesy shows like
''World's Most Dangerous Animals.'' After the quickie marriage of
Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger fell apart on ''Multimillionaire,''
the network has moved cautiously into a programming area dominated
by CBS this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very difficult to create objective standards by which to
conduct one's business in this area,'' Grushow told reporters.
''It's very subjective.
</P>
<P>
   Whether something is appropriate to air is ''like the old
Supreme Court definition of pornography -- you know it when you see
it,'' he said. ''And it's our jobs to make sure that we're policing
our own airwaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Fox premieres ''American High,'' a summer-run series
showing the true-life experiences of students in a Chicago-area
suburban high school. It will also air ''The Sexiest Bachelor in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Among series in the works at Fox are ''I Want a Divorce,'' in
which real-life couples who are splitting up compete for their
shared property, and ''Master Game,'' a game show in which
contestants battle fatigue like students cramming for college
finals.
</P>
<P>
   But consider the shows that Fox had developed but that Grushow
said have been permanently shelved: ''World's Meanest Ladies,''
''Plastic Surgery Nightmares'' and ''Cheating Spouses Caught on
Tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives admitted that they -- and other networks -- passed
on the CBS hit ''Survivor'' when it was offered a year and a half
ago. No explanation was given.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has suffered in the ratings this year, with the new comedy
''Malcolm in the Middle'' one of the few bright spots. Its schedule
underwent the biggest overhaul of the broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know we're at the beginning of a major rebuilding
process,'' Grushow said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 2204 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
