<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegate Booted From Convention  </HEADLINE>
By GINA HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Her race and Mississippi's once
whites-only political machine kept Mamie Cunningham out of the 1964
Democratic National Convention. This time gender will sideline her
at the party's presidential bash.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham was pulled as a delegate to next month's 2000
convention in Los Angeles because Mississippi's racially diverse
delegation would have had two more women than men.
</P>
<P>
   The north Mississippi school teacher, elected a delegate in May,
was told this week she will be making the trip as an alternate.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a purpose for the rules. The people who were not
represented in the past, now they are represented,'' said Balwant
Singh of Pascagoula, who challenged the delegate selections.
''Women were ignored in the past, now they have rights. Blacks were
ignored, now they have rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh was mainly contesting his failure to make the delegation,
but a review found the gender imbalance. The retired educator is
Asian American, and he said the delegation includes only black and
white men although one slot is traditionally reserved for someone
from another race.
</P>
<P>
   The ouster is reminiscent of Cunningham's last convention
experience, when as a college coed she joined black Freedom
Democrats in a convention trip to challenge the all-white regular
state party for refusing to accept black delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham recalls being an observer in a group that included
Fannie Lou Hamer and other civil rights activists. She said they
watched the convention in Atlantic City from ''the window out on
the street and the boardwalk, picking up bits of information from
people who had been inside.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Democratic convention, ''I'm going to be more or less an
observer again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders replaced Cunningham with state Sen. David
Jordan of Greenwood after Singh filed his challenge with the
Democratic National Committee and the presidential campaign of Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders said that if the state delegation does not meet
gender guidelines, delegates could risk not being allowed at the
convention. The DNC notified Mississippi officials about the
problem last week.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, a 58-year-old mother of three who teaches in
Aberdeen, was a student at Rust College in 1964 when she went to
the convention against her parents advice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 2206 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
