<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki Campaign Aide Denies Scheme  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A campaign aide to Gov. George Pataki repeatedly
denied Thursday that he helped to arrange early release of violent
felons in exchange for political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Donohue, finance director for a group called Friends of
Pataki, testified as a defense witness in a campaign corruption
trial of Korean-American businessman Yung Soo Yoo.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors allege Yoo brokered deals to guarantee to
three sets of Korean-American parents that campaign contributions
totaling $36,000 would result in parole for their inmate sons.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Donohue's lawyer, Tom Puccio, called the
pay-for-parole probe a ''witchhunt'' in which his innocent client
was being used ''to tar Mr. Yoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue has not been charged with any crime, and the governor's
office denies any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   On the stand, Donohue admitted meeting with a pastor whose son,
convicted robber and gang member John Kim, was paroled in 1996
after the family arranged for $7,000 in donations to the Pataki
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue testified he was unaware the donors had a child in
prison and said he returned the money when he learned they thought
there was quid pro quo.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors used internal memos, testimony by the parents and
secretly recorded conversations in an attempt to show that Donohue
illicitly lobbied for the prisoners' release. Donohue said he
contacted administration insiders about the inmates only to help
the families learn more about their legal status.
</P>
<P>
   Three parole officials have been charged or convicted in the
grand jury investigation of alleged influence peddling.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo, 63, of Glen Ridge, N.J., faces up to 10 years in prison if
convicted on corruption and obstruction of justice charges.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue, 29, has continued raising money for Pataki, the
Republican party and Senate hopeful Rick Lazio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
