<HEADLINE> Denver Mayor Seeks Intervention  </HEADLINE>
By COLLEEN SLEVIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The city's mayor on Thursday asked the U.S.
transportation secretary to help solve labor problems at United
Airlines that have delayed and stranded passengers at Denver
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Weather was partly responsible for the delays, but Mayor
Wellington Webb also blamed labor negotiations with pilots and
mechanics and alleged slowdowns by air traffic controllers at
Chicago's O'Hare airport.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, who sent a letter to Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater Thursday, did not side with labor or United.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know whose fault it is that we're not flying,'' said
Webb, whose own recent flight on United was delayed by 4&AMP;frac12; hours.
</P>
<P>
   United spokesman Joe Hopkins said federal mediators are already
involved in the negotiations with pilots.
</P>
<P>
   He would not comment on what else Slater could do to help
negotiations with mechanics. Neither side has requested mediation
in those talks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Department spokeswoman Mary Trupo said the agency
normally does not get involved in labor issues but is watching
United closely.
</P>
<P>
   Trupo said the problems in Chicago, which she blamed on
''renegade'' controllers, are still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''That little episode, I don't think we'll be seeing that
replayed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, hundreds of flights were canceled or delayed for
hours at O'Hare. The Chicago Tribune reported that a local work
slowdown by air traffic controllers, unrelated to the United
negotiations, was to blame. A union official denied that.
</P>
<P>
   United's parent company acknowledged this week an ''abnormally
high rate of delays and cancellations'' in announcing a drop in
second-quarter earnings from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   United spokesman Chris Braithwaite said about 100 flights were
canceled Thursday out of 2,400 domestic flights nationwide. In
Denver, seven out of 317 scheduled departures were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance-related flight cancellations more than doubled
nationwide after the mechanics' contract expired July 12, a United
vice president said in a letter circulated within the company.
</P>
<P>
   The official blamed the cancellations on mechanics' refusing to
work overtime and writing more reports on potential aircraft
problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
