<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Wary of West Nile Virus  </HEADLINE>
By JUDIE GLAVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tests have shown that a man who died after
reporting symptoms similar to those of the West Nile virus did not
have the disease, but the city remained vigilant for signs of the
potentially deadly illness.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of the mosquito-borne virus, which killed seven people in
the New York area last summer, was causing subtle changes in life
in Staten Island, the only city borough where the disease has shown
up this year. Two dead crows were found to have carried the virus.
</P>
<P>
   At the Friends day care center Thursday, the ball pit was empty
and the wavy, red slide was abandoned by the toddlers whose giggles
can usually be heard. Workers at the wooded Clay Pit Ponds State
Park Preserve armed themselves with cans of bug repellent.
</P>
<P>
   Adriana Robotti told her three daughters to stay out of their
pool because the city had sprayed the insecticide Anvil in the area
to kill mosquitoes. She was not only concerned about the pesticide,
but also mosquito bites.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel a little like a mosquito myself -- trapped,'' Robotti
said Thursday. ''I can't lock the kids in the house the rest of the
summer. It's crazy and more than a little scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns were heightened after a 71-year-old man visiting from
South Carolina died Wednesday on Staten Island after being
hospitalized with West Nile-like symptoms: muscle aches, stiff neck
and flu-like ailments.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Thursday that tests for West
Nile came back negative.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile can result in encephalitis, or a swelling of the
brain. The elderly and those with weak immune systems are most at
risk.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta has recommended mosquito control, including aerial
spraying, in a two-mile radius of infected birds and mosquitos to
help avoid transmission of the virus to people.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen dead, infected birds have been found in
parts of two suburban counties, Westchester and Rockland;
virus-carrying mosquitoes were found in Suffolk County, on Long
Island. All three counties have plans to spray.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups and activists are suing the city in an
attempt to stop the spraying, claiming the insecticide is harmful
to humans, fish and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ''We find that these insecticides they are spraying are far
worse than any kind of ailment in the city,'' Mitchell Cohen, a
member of the No Spray Coalition Against the Misuse of Pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Daidone, the co-owner of the Friends preschool and day care
center, was taking all precautions against bugs and the spray. She
kept the dozen preschoolers in her care inside Thursday instead of
playing in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hate keeping them inside on such a beautiful summer day,''
she said, ''but I'm not taking any chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 2220 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
