<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottey Wins Heats at Olympic Trials  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) -- Merlene Ottey, at age 40 trying to
qualify for her sixth Olympic team, advanced to the semifinals of
100 meters Thursday at Jamaica's Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   She won her heat in 11.09 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Monaco-based Ottey's second race -- and first in
Jamaica -- since being cleared of drug use by an International
Amateur Athletics Federation panel on July 10. Track and field's
world governing body reinstated her after a year's ban, concluding
that a Swiss laboratory had improperly tested her urine sample when
she came up positive for the steroid nandrolone at a meet in
Switzerland in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Ottey, who has kept a low profile since arriving in Jamaica five
days ago, had a slow start but made up ground on runner-up Tanya
Lawrence then eased up at the line for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ''With 30 meters to go I was in a daze, but I got going and it
was easy after that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She needs to finish in the top three of Friday's 100 final to
qualify for the event at the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Jamaica Amateur Athletics Association, who long
ago cleared Ottey of the drug charges, have said the double silver
medalist at the 1996 Games would likely be included on their
Olympic squad even if she fails to place among the top three
finishers or post the required time of 11.40.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at a regional meet in Sardinia, Italy, Ottey won the
100 in a slow 11.42.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
