<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nature Conservancy expands St. John River protection  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ORONO, Maine (AP) - The Nature Conservancy has struck land deals
with northern Maine landowners to protect additional areas along
remote sections of the St. John River.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with J.M. Huber Corp. adds more than two miles of river
protection within a 6,000-acre acquisition, the nonprofit
conservation organization announced Thursday. The transaction
involved the exchange of land and timber rights.
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy swapped its ownership of land that didn't abut
the river for J.M. Huber's ownership of land along the river. The
land the conservancy gave up was not as valuable ecologically or
recreationally as the land along the river, said Kent Wommack,
executive director of the Nature Conservancy's Maine chapter.
</P>
<P>
   J.M. Huber then donated a conservation easement on 36,000 acres
of land in the river's watershed that will ensure that the area
isn't developed, the conservation group said. The company, based in
Edison, N.J., has operations in Easton, Old Town and Millinocket.
</P>
<P>
   The company and its workers want the river ''to be enjoyed by
all who love the wilds of Maine as we do,'' said Gerry Collins,
J.M. Huber's vice president of natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate 7,000-acre deal, the Nature Conservancy also
acquired partial ownership of land over which the upper St. John
River runs for about 17 miles through Dunn Timberlands.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sawyer, president of Dunn Timberlands, was a member of
the committee that drew up the river's resource protection plan
that has guided timber operations since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The Dunn agreement involved having the conservancy buy out a
Dunn heir's share of lands for between $1 million and $1.5 million,
which it borrowed from its Land Preservation Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The heir did not want the exact amount made public, Wommack
said. The conservancy also agreed to swap its interest in land that
doesn't abut the river for Dunn's interest in riverside land,
Wommack said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dunn agreement and the J.M. Huber deal expands the
conservation group's ownership interest in lands abutting the river
from 40 to 60 miles, or 40,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best conservation deals are struck when the parties
respect one another's needs and intentions,'' Wommack said.
</P>
<P>
   The land deals announced Thursday are the first Nature
Conservancy acquisitions along the river since it bought 185,000
acres from International Paper in 1998. The conservancy borrowed
$35 million from its Land Preservation Fund for the purchase, its
largest financial commitment to any project. It has raised $32
million so far to pay back the loan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-20-00 2302 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000720.0230 </DOCNO>
