<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Governor Talks With Miller  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes has discussed the
state's vacant Senate seat with his predecessor, Zell Miller,
political sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in both political parties said the two men met
Wednesday, one day after the death of Republican Sen. Paul
Coverdell. There was no indication whether Barnes offered to use
his authority under state law to appoint Miller to the Senate
pending a special election on Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 68, has not indicated an interest in returning to public
life since leaving office in January 1999. He declined earlier in
the week to discuss the vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, 61, succumbed on Tuesday to the effects of a cerebral
hemorrhage. Discreet maneuvering over the vacancy began even before
memorial services scheduled for this weekend in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, several sources identified Rep. Johnny
Isakson as a potential candidate. In an interview, Isakson declined
to discuss the race. ''It's not really an appropriate time,'' he
said. ''There's a time and place for everything, but this isn't
it.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP Rep. Jack Kingston said he had received calls asking if he
was going to run, ''but I'm still in the shellshocked stage of
grief.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats, Rep. John Lewis, a veteran of the civil rights
movement, signaled an interest, as did other political figures in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller, 68, who served two terms as governor, also surfaced
quickly in the speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to talk about anything like that,'' he said
earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans currently control the Senate with a majority of
54-45. While Democrats are well-positioned to gain seats in the
fall elections, Coverdell's death creates an opening that could
permit them to creep closer, if not challenge the GOP for control.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, several Democrats, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said during the day they hoped Miller could be persuaded to accept
appointment and then run in the November election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-20-00 2354 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000720.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alabama Temps Break 100 Again  </HEADLINE>
By JAY REEVES
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- With only two little fans to cool her
cinderblock home, Willie Shepard sweltered along with the rest of
the sun-baked South on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 78-year-old woman finally gave up on getting cool inside the
six-room house and moved instead to the circle of shade under a
small tree, hoping to catch a noontime breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Wiping away sweat, Shepard recalled her fitful sleep the night
before. ''I got so hot I went and put my head in the
refrigerator,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a record-breaking heat wave already blamed for at least 16
deaths across the region, Shepard's hometown of Tuscaloosa was an
oven turned on high. On Thursday, the temperature broke the
100-degree mark for the 16th straight day.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, Tuscaloosa and much of Alabama got some
badly needed relief as a line of thunderstorms rolled through the
state, dropping temperatures as much as 30 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-moving storm, with winds up to 60 mph, brought
Tuscaloosa almost as much rain -- 1.67 inches -- as the city had seen
in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Storms in Arkansas also brought wind gusts as high as 80 mph.
The mother of a state senator was killed when a tree was blown onto
her car.
</P>
<P>
   Much more rain is still needed to overcome the extreme drought
that is killing crops across much of the South, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   The two weeks of blistering heat have been blamed for at least
12 deaths in Texas and four in Louisiana. Forecasters said most
areas should cool down heading into the weekend, but only by a few
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   About 8,500 homes and businesses in Tulsa, Okla., lost power
Thursday during a thunderstorm that signaled an approaching front.
In Texas, Dallas County remained under an emergency health alert
prompted by temperatures above 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, temperatures have been running five to 10 degrees
above normal. Columbus has been the state's hot spot, with 100-plus
temperatures for six days.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuscaloosa, the county welfare office has seen an increase in
cases of neglect of the elderly, possibly because the heat has made
people too stressed or tired to take care of others. More than 20
instances of neglect have been reported in the last month, about
twice as many as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's the heat,'' said Ken Sanders, adult services
supervisor for the Tuscaloosa County Department of Human Resources.
''After a while, people begin to get heat fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   While the South baked, it was still sweater weather in Michigan.
Temperatures in the southeastern part of the state have averaged 14
degrees below normal this month -- and all-time July lows were set
Wednesday in two cities in the Upper Peninsula: 34 in Manistique
and 36 in Escanaba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
